 110 def _make_comparison_op(op, cls):
 111     def cmp_method(self, other):
 112         if isinstance(other, (np.ndarray, Index, ABCSeries, ExtensionArray)):
 113             if other.ndim > 0 and len(self) != len(other):
 114                 raise ValueError("Lengths must match to compare")
 115 
 116         if is_object_dtype(self.dtype) and isinstance(other, ABCCategorical):
 117             left = type(other)(self._values, dtype=other.dtype)
 118             return op(left, other)
 119         elif is_object_dtype(self.dtype) and isinstance(other, ExtensionArray):
 120             # e.g. PeriodArray
 121             with np.errstate(all="ignore"):
 122                 result = op(self._values, other)
 123 
 124         elif is_object_dtype(self.dtype) and not isinstance(self, ABCMultiIndex):
 125             # don't pass MultiIndex
 126             with np.errstate(all="ignore"):
 127                 result = ops.comp_method_OBJECT_ARRAY(op, self._values, other)
 128 
 129         else:
 130             with np.errstate(all="ignore"):
 131                 result = op(self._values, np.asarray(other))
 132 
 133         if is_bool_dtype(result):
 134             return result
 135         return ops.invalid_comparison(self, other, op)
 136 
 137     name = f"__{op.__name__}__"
 138     return set_function_name(cmp_method, name, cls)
 139 
 140 
 141 def _make_arithmetic_op(op, cls):
 142     def index_arithmetic_method(self, other):
 143         if isinstance(other, (ABCSeries, ABCDataFrame, ABCTimedeltaIndex)):
 144             return NotImplemented
 145 
 146         from pandas import Series
 147 
 148         result = op(Series(self), other)
 149         if isinstance(result, tuple):
 150             return (Index(result[0]), Index(result[1]))
 151         return Index(result)
 152 
 153     name = f"__{op.__name__}__"
 154     return set_function_name(index_arithmetic_method, name, cls)

 161 def _new_Index(cls, d):
 162     """
 163     This is called upon unpickling, rather than the default which doesn't
 164     have arguments and breaks __new__.
 165     """
 166     # required for backward compat, because PI can't be instantiated with
 167     # ordinals through __new__ GH #13277
 168     if issubclass(cls, ABCPeriodIndex):
 169         from pandas.core.indexes.period import _new_PeriodIndex
 170 
 171         return _new_PeriodIndex(cls, **d)
 172 
 173     if issubclass(cls, ABCMultiIndex):
 174         if "labels" in d and "codes" not in d:
 175             # GH#23752 "labels" kwarg has been replaced with "codes"
 176             d["codes"] = d.pop("labels")
 177 
 178     return cls.__new__(cls, **d)

 181 class Index(IndexOpsMixin, PandasObject):
 182     """
 183     Immutable ndarray implementing an ordered, sliceable set. The basic object
 184     storing axis labels for all pandas objects.
 185 
 186     Parameters
 187     ----------
 188     data : array-like (1-dimensional)
 189     dtype : NumPy dtype (default: object)
 190         If dtype is None, we find the dtype that best fits the data.
 191         If an actual dtype is provided, we coerce to that dtype if it's safe.
 192         Otherwise, an error will be raised.
 193     copy : bool
 194         Make a copy of input ndarray.
 195     name : object
 196         Name to be stored in the index.
 197     tupleize_cols : bool (default: True)
 198         When True, attempt to create a MultiIndex if possible.
 199 
 200     See Also
 201     --------
 202     RangeIndex : Index implementing a monotonic integer range.
 203     CategoricalIndex : Index of :class:`Categorical` s.
 204     MultiIndex : A multi-level, or hierarchical Index.
 205     IntervalIndex : An Index of :class:`Interval` s.
 206     DatetimeIndex : Index of datetime64 data.
 207     TimedeltaIndex : Index of timedelta64 data.
 208     PeriodIndex : Index of Period data.
 209     Int64Index : A special case of :class:`Index` with purely integer labels.
 210     UInt64Index : A special case of :class:`Index` with purely unsigned integer labels.
 211     Float64Index : A special case of :class:`Index` with purely float labels.
 212 
 213     Notes
 214     -----
 215     An Index instance can **only** contain hashable objects
 216 
 217     Examples
 218     --------
 219     >>> pd.Index([1, 2, 3])
 220     Int64Index([1, 2, 3], dtype='int64')
 221 
 222     >>> pd.Index(list('abc'))
 223     Index(['a', 'b', 'c'], dtype='object')
 224     """
 225 
 226     # tolist is not actually deprecated, just suppressed in the __dir__
 227     _deprecations: FrozenSet[str] = (
 228         PandasObject._deprecations
 229         | IndexOpsMixin._deprecations
 230         | frozenset(["contains", "set_value"])
 231     )
 232 
 233     # To hand over control to subclasses
 234     _join_precedence = 1
 235 
 236     # Cython methods; see github.com/cython/cython/issues/2647
 237     #  for why we need to wrap these instead of making them class attributes
 238     # Moreover, cython will choose the appropriate-dtyped sub-function
 239     #  given the dtypes of the passed arguments
 240     def _left_indexer_unique(self, left, right):
 241         return libjoin.left_join_indexer_unique(left, right)
 242 
 243     def _left_indexer(self, left, right):
 244         return libjoin.left_join_indexer(left, right)
 245 
 246     def _inner_indexer(self, left, right):
 247         return libjoin.inner_join_indexer(left, right)
 248 
 249     def _outer_indexer(self, left, right):
 250         return libjoin.outer_join_indexer(left, right)
 251 
 252     _typ = "index"
 253     _data: Union[ExtensionArray, np.ndarray]
 254     _id = None
 255     _name: Label = None
 256     # MultiIndex.levels previously allowed setting the index name. We
 257     # don't allow this anymore, and raise if it happens rather than
 258     # failing silently.
 259     _no_setting_name: bool = False
 260     _comparables = ["name"]
 261     _attributes = ["name"]
 262     _is_numeric_dtype = False
 263     _can_hold_na = True
 264 
 265     # would we like our indexing holder to defer to us
 266     _defer_to_indexing = False
 267 
 268     _engine_type = libindex.ObjectEngine
 269     # whether we support partial string indexing. Overridden
 270     # in DatetimeIndex and PeriodIndex
 271     _supports_partial_string_indexing = False
 272 
 273     _accessors = {"str"}
 274 
 275     str = CachedAccessor("str", StringMethods)
 276 
 277     # --------------------------------------------------------------------
 278     # Constructors
 279 
 280     def __new__(
 281         cls, data=None, dtype=None, copy=False, name=None, tupleize_cols=True, **kwargs
 282     ) -> "Index":
 283 
 284         from pandas.core.indexes.range import RangeIndex
 285 
 286         name = maybe_extract_name(name, data, cls)
 287 
 288         if dtype is not None:
 289             dtype = pandas_dtype(dtype)
 290         if "tz" in kwargs:
 291             tz = kwargs.pop("tz")
 292             validate_tz_from_dtype(dtype, tz)
 293             dtype = tz_to_dtype(tz)
 294 
 295         if isinstance(data, ABCPandasArray):
 296             # ensure users don't accidentally put a PandasArray in an index.
 297             data = data.to_numpy()
 298 
 299         data_dtype = getattr(data, "dtype", None)
 300 
 301         # range
 302         if isinstance(data, RangeIndex):
 303             return RangeIndex(start=data, copy=copy, dtype=dtype, name=name)
 304         elif isinstance(data, range):
 305             return RangeIndex.from_range(data, dtype=dtype, name=name)
 306 
 307         # categorical
 308         elif is_categorical_dtype(data_dtype) or is_categorical_dtype(dtype):
 309             # Delay import for perf. https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/31423
 310             from pandas.core.indexes.category import CategoricalIndex
 311 
 312             return _maybe_asobject(dtype, CategoricalIndex, data, copy, name, **kwargs)
 313 
 314         # interval
 315         elif is_interval_dtype(data_dtype) or is_interval_dtype(dtype):
 316             # Delay import for perf. https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/31423
 317             from pandas.core.indexes.interval import IntervalIndex
 318 
 319             return _maybe_asobject(dtype, IntervalIndex, data, copy, name, **kwargs)
 320 
 321         elif is_datetime64_any_dtype(data_dtype) or is_datetime64_any_dtype(dtype):
 322             # Delay import for perf. https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/31423
 323             from pandas import DatetimeIndex
 324 
 325             return _maybe_asobject(dtype, DatetimeIndex, data, copy, name, **kwargs)
 326 
 327         elif is_timedelta64_dtype(data_dtype) or is_timedelta64_dtype(dtype):
 328             # Delay import for perf. https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/31423
 329             from pandas import TimedeltaIndex
 330 
 331             return _maybe_asobject(dtype, TimedeltaIndex, data, copy, name, **kwargs)
 332 
 333         elif is_period_dtype(data_dtype) or is_period_dtype(dtype):
 334             # Delay import for perf. https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/31423
 335             from pandas import PeriodIndex
 336 
 337             return _maybe_asobject(dtype, PeriodIndex, data, copy, name, **kwargs)
 338 
 339         # extension dtype
 340         elif is_extension_array_dtype(data_dtype) or is_extension_array_dtype(dtype):
 341             if not (dtype is None or is_object_dtype(dtype)):
 342                 # coerce to the provided dtype
 343                 ea_cls = dtype.construct_array_type()
 344                 data = ea_cls._from_sequence(data, dtype=dtype, copy=False)
 345             else:
 346                 data = np.asarray(data, dtype=object)
 347 
 348             # coerce to the object dtype
 349             data = data.astype(object)
 350             return Index(data, dtype=object, copy=copy, name=name, **kwargs)
 351 
 352         # index-like
 353         elif isinstance(data, (np.ndarray, Index, ABCSeries)):
 354             # Delay import for perf. https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/31423
 355             from pandas.core.indexes.numeric import (
 356                 Float64Index,
 357                 Int64Index,
 358                 UInt64Index,
 359             )
 360 
 361             if dtype is not None:
 362                 # we need to avoid having numpy coerce
 363                 # things that look like ints/floats to ints unless
 364                 # they are actually ints, e.g. '0' and 0.0
 365                 # should not be coerced
 366                 # GH 11836
 367                 data = _maybe_cast_with_dtype(data, dtype, copy)
 368                 dtype = data.dtype  # TODO: maybe not for object?
 369 
 370             # maybe coerce to a sub-class
 371             if is_signed_integer_dtype(data.dtype):
 372                 return Int64Index(data, copy=copy, dtype=dtype, name=name)
 373             elif is_unsigned_integer_dtype(data.dtype):
 374                 return UInt64Index(data, copy=copy, dtype=dtype, name=name)
 375             elif is_float_dtype(data.dtype):
 376                 return Float64Index(data, copy=copy, dtype=dtype, name=name)
 377             elif issubclass(data.dtype.type, np.bool) or is_bool_dtype(data):
 378                 subarr = data.astype("object")
 379             else:
 380                 subarr = com.asarray_tuplesafe(data, dtype=object)
 381 
 382             # asarray_tuplesafe does not always copy underlying data,
 383             # so need to make sure that this happens
 384             if copy:
 385                 subarr = subarr.copy()
 386 
 387             if dtype is None:
 388                 new_data, new_dtype = _maybe_cast_data_without_dtype(subarr)
 389                 if new_dtype is not None:
 390                     return cls(
 391                         new_data, dtype=new_dtype, copy=False, name=name, **kwargs
 392                     )
 393 
 394             if kwargs:
 395                 raise TypeError(f"Unexpected keyword arguments {repr(set(kwargs))}")
 396             if subarr.ndim > 1:
 397                 # GH#13601, GH#20285, GH#27125
 398                 raise ValueError("Index data must be 1-dimensional")
 399             return cls._simple_new(subarr, name)
 400 
 401         elif data is None or is_scalar(data):
 402             raise cls._scalar_data_error(data)
 403         elif hasattr(data, "__array__"):
 404             return Index(np.asarray(data), dtype=dtype, copy=copy, name=name, **kwargs)
 405         else:
 406             if tupleize_cols and is_list_like(data):
 407                 # GH21470: convert iterable to list before determining if empty
 408                 if is_iterator(data):
 409                     data = list(data)
 410 
 411                 if data and all(isinstance(e, tuple) for e in data):
 412                     # we must be all tuples, otherwise don't construct
 413                     # 10697
 414                     from pandas.core.indexes.multi import MultiIndex
 415 
 416                     return MultiIndex.from_tuples(
 417                         data, names=name or kwargs.get("names")
 418                     )
 419             # other iterable of some kind
 420             subarr = com.asarray_tuplesafe(data, dtype=object)
 421             return Index(subarr, dtype=dtype, copy=copy, name=name, **kwargs)
 422 
 423     """
 424     NOTE for new Index creation:
 425 
 426     - _simple_new: It returns new Index with the same type as the caller.
 427       All metadata (such as name) must be provided by caller's responsibility.
 428       Using _shallow_copy is recommended because it fills these metadata
 429       otherwise specified.
 430 
 431     - _shallow_copy: It returns new Index with the same type (using
 432       _simple_new), but fills caller's metadata otherwise specified. Passed
 433       kwargs will overwrite corresponding metadata.
 434 
 435     See each method's docstring.
 436     """
 437 
 438     @property
 439     def asi8(self):
 440         """
 441         Integer representation of the values.
 442 
 443         Returns
 444         -------
 445         ndarray
 446             An ndarray with int64 dtype.
 447         """
 448         return None
 449 
 450     @classmethod
 451     def _simple_new(cls, values, name: Label = None):
 452         """
 453         We require that we have a dtype compat for the values. If we are passed
 454         a non-dtype compat, then coerce using the constructor.
 455 
 456         Must be careful not to recurse.
 457         """
 458         assert isinstance(values, np.ndarray), type(values)
 459 
 460         result = object.__new__(cls)
 461         result._data = values
 462         # _index_data is a (temporary?) fix to ensure that the direct data
 463         # manipulation we do in `_libs/reduction.pyx` continues to work.
 464         # We need access to the actual ndarray, since we're messing with
 465         # data buffers and strides.
 466         result._index_data = values
 467         result._name = name
 468         result._cache = {}
 469 
 470         return result._reset_identity()
 471 
 472     @cache_readonly
 473     def _constructor(self):
 474         return type(self)

 479     def _get_attributes_dict(self):
 480         """
 481         Return an attributes dict for my class.
 482         """
 483         return {k: getattr(self, k, None) for k in self._attributes}
 484 
 485     def _shallow_copy(self, values=None, name: Label = no_default):
 486         """
 487         Create a new Index with the same class as the caller, don't copy the
 488         data, use the same object attributes with passed in attributes taking
 489         precedence.
 490 
 491         *this is an internal non-public method*
 492 
 493         Parameters
 494         ----------
 495         values : the values to create the new Index, optional
 496         name : Label, defaults to self.name
 497         """
 498         name = self.name if name is no_default else name
 499         cache = self._cache.copy() if values is None else {}
 500         if values is None:
 501             values = self._values
 502 
 503         result = self._simple_new(values, name=name)
 504         result._cache = cache
 505         return result
 506 
 507     def is_(self, other) -> bool:
 508         """
 509         More flexible, faster check like ``is`` but that works through views.
 510 
 511         Note: this is *not* the same as ``Index.identical()``, which checks
 512         that metadata is also the same.
 513 
 514         Parameters
 515         ----------
 516         other : object
 517             Other object to compare against.
 518 
 519         Returns
 520         -------
 521         True if both have same underlying data, False otherwise : bool
 522         """
 523         # use something other than None to be clearer
 524         return self._id is getattr(other, "_id", Ellipsis) and self._id is not None

 527         """
 528         Initializes or resets ``_id`` attribute with new object.
 529         """
 530         self._id = _Identity()
 531         return self

 538         # property, for now, slow to look up

 542         target_values = self._get_engine_target()

 561     def __array_wrap__(self, result, context=None):
 562         """
 563         Gets called after a ufunc.

 566         if is_bool_dtype(result) or lib.is_scalar(result) or np.ndim(result) > 1:

 595     def view(self, cls=None):
 596 
 597         # we need to see if we are subclassing an
 598         # index type here
 599         if cls is not None and not hasattr(cls, "_typ"):
 600             result = self._data.view(cls)

 607     def astype(self, dtype, copy=True):
 608         """
 609         Create an Index with values cast to dtypes.
 610 
 611         The class of a new Index is determined by dtype. When conversion is
 612         impossible, a ValueError exception is raised.
 613 
 614         Parameters
 615         ----------
 616         dtype : numpy dtype or pandas type
 617             Note that any signed integer `dtype` is treated as ``'int64'``,
 618             and any unsigned integer `dtype` is treated as ``'uint64'``,
 619             regardless of the size.
 620         copy : bool, default True
 621             By default, astype always returns a newly allocated object.
 622             If copy is set to False and internal requirements on dtype are
 623             satisfied, the original data is used to create a new Index
 624             or the original Index is returned.
 625 
 626         Returns
 627         -------
 628         Index
 629             Index with values cast to specified dtype.
 630         """
 631         if dtype is not None:
 632             dtype = pandas_dtype(dtype)
 633 
 634         if is_dtype_equal(self.dtype, dtype):
 635             return self.copy() if copy else self
 636 
 637         elif is_categorical_dtype(dtype):
 638             from pandas.core.indexes.category import CategoricalIndex
 639 
 640             return CategoricalIndex(
 641                 self._values, name=self.name, dtype=dtype, copy=copy
 642             )
 643 
 644         elif is_extension_array_dtype(dtype):
 645             return Index(np.asarray(self), name=self.name, dtype=dtype, copy=copy)
 646 
 647         try:
 648             casted = self._values.astype(dtype, copy=copy)
 649         except (TypeError, ValueError) as err:
 650             raise TypeError(
 651                 f"Cannot cast {type(self).__name__} to dtype {dtype}"
 652             ) from err
 653         return Index(casted, name=self.name, dtype=dtype)

 655     _index_shared_docs[
 656         "take"
 657     ] = """
 658         Return a new %(klass)s of the values selected by the indices.
 659 
 660         For internal compatibility with numpy arrays.
 661 
 662         Parameters
 663         ----------
 664         indices : list
 665             Indices to be taken.
 666         axis : int, optional
 667             The axis over which to select values, always 0.
 668         allow_fill : bool, default True
 669         fill_value : bool, default None
 670             If allow_fill=True and fill_value is not None, indices specified by
 671             -1 is regarded as NA. If Index doesn't hold NA, raise ValueError.
 672 
 673         Returns
 674         -------
 675         numpy.ndarray
 676             Elements of given indices.
 677 
 678         See Also
 679         --------
 680         numpy.ndarray.take
 681         """

 683     @Appender(_index_shared_docs["take"] % _index_doc_kwargs)
 684     def take(self, indices, axis=0, allow_fill=True, fill_value=None, **kwargs):
 685         if kwargs:
 686             nv.validate_take(tuple(), kwargs)
 687         indices = ensure_platform_int(indices)
 688         if self._can_hold_na:
 689             taken = self._assert_take_fillable(
 690                 self._values,
 691                 indices,
 692                 allow_fill=allow_fill,
 693                 fill_value=fill_value,
 694                 na_value=self._na_value,
 695             )
 696         else:
 697             if allow_fill and fill_value is not None:
 698                 cls_name = type(self).__name__
 699                 raise ValueError(
 700                     f"Unable to fill values because {cls_name} cannot contain NA"
 701                 )
 702             taken = self._values.take(indices)
 703         return self._shallow_copy(taken)
 704 
 705     def _assert_take_fillable(
 706         self, values, indices, allow_fill=True, fill_value=None, na_value=np.nan
 707     ):
 708         """
 709         Internal method to handle NA filling of take.
 710         """
 711         indices = ensure_platform_int(indices)
 712 
 713         # only fill if we are passing a non-None fill_value
 714         if allow_fill and fill_value is not None:
 715             if (indices < -1).any():
 716                 raise ValueError(
 717                     "When allow_fill=True and fill_value is not None, "
 718                     "all indices must be >= -1"
 719                 )
 720             taken = algos.take(
 721                 values, indices, allow_fill=allow_fill, fill_value=na_value
 722             )
 723         else:
 724             taken = values.take(indices)
 725         return taken

 775     def copy(self, name=None, deep=False, dtype=None, names=None):
 776         """
 777         Make a copy of this object.
 778 
 779         Name and dtype sets those attributes on the new object.
 780 
 781         Parameters
 782         ----------
 783         name : Label, optional
 784             Set name for new object.
 785         deep : bool, default False
 786         dtype : numpy dtype or pandas type, optional
 787             Set dtype for new object.
 788         names : list-like, optional
 789             Kept for compatibility with MultiIndex. Should not be used.
 790 
 791         Returns
 792         -------
 793         Index
 794             Index refer to new object which is a copy of this object.
 795 
 796         Notes
 797         -----
 798         In most cases, there should be no functional difference from using
 799         ``deep``, but if ``deep`` is passed it will attempt to deepcopy.
 800         """
 801         if deep:
 802             new_index = self._shallow_copy(self._data.copy())
 803         else:
 804             new_index = self._shallow_copy()
 805 
 806         names = self._validate_names(name=name, names=names, deep=deep)
 807         new_index = new_index.set_names(names)
 808 
 809         if dtype:
 810             new_index = new_index.astype(dtype)
 811         return new_index

 828     def __repr__(self) -> str_t:
 829         """
 830         Return a string representation for this object.
 831         """
 832         klass_name = type(self).__name__
 833         data = self._format_data()
 834         attrs = self._format_attrs()
 835         space = self._format_space()
 836         attrs_str = [f"{k}={v}" for k, v in attrs]
 837         prepr = f",{space}".join(attrs_str)
 838 
 839         # no data provided, just attributes
 840         if data is None:
 841             data = ""
 842 
 843         res = f"{klass_name}({data}{prepr})"
 844 
 845         return res
 846 
 847     def _format_space(self) -> str_t:
 848 
 849         # using space here controls if the attributes
 850         # are line separated or not (the default)
 851 
 852         # max_seq_items = get_option('display.max_seq_items')
 853         # if len(self) > max_seq_items:
 854         #    space = "\n%s" % (' ' * (len(klass) + 1))
 855         return " "

 864     def _format_data(self, name=None) -> str_t:
 865         """
 866         Return the formatted data as a unicode string.
 867         """
 868         # do we want to justify (only do so for non-objects)
 869         is_justify = True
 870 
 871         if self.inferred_type == "string":
 872             is_justify = False
 873         elif self.inferred_type == "categorical":
 874             if is_object_dtype(self.categories):  # type: ignore
 875                 is_justify = False
 876 
 877         return format_object_summary(
 878             self, self._formatter_func, is_justify=is_justify, name=name
 879         )

 891     def format(self, name: bool = False, formatter=None, **kwargs):
 892         """
 893         Render a string representation of the Index.
 894         """
 895         header = []
 896         if name:
 897             header.append(
 898                 pprint_thing(self.name, escape_chars=("\t", "\r", "\n"))
 899                 if self.name is not None
 900                 else ""
 901             )
 902 
 903         if formatter is not None:
 904             return header + list(self.map(formatter))
 905 
 906         return self._format_with_header(header, **kwargs)
 907 
 908     def _format_with_header(self, header, na_rep="NaN", **kwargs):
 909         values = self._values
 910 
 911         from pandas.io.formats.format import format_array
 912 
 913         if is_categorical_dtype(values.dtype):
 914             values = np.array(values)
 915 
 916         elif is_object_dtype(values.dtype):
 917             values = lib.maybe_convert_objects(values, safe=1)
 918 
 919         if is_object_dtype(values.dtype):
 920             result = [pprint_thing(x, escape_chars=("\t", "\r", "\n")) for x in values]
 921 
 922             # could have nans
 923             mask = isna(values)
 924             if mask.any():
 925                 result = np.array(result)
 926                 result[mask] = na_rep
 927                 result = result.tolist()
 928 
 929         else:
 930             result = _trim_front(format_array(values, None, justify="left"))
 931         return header + result

 933     def to_native_types(self, slicer=None, **kwargs):
 934         """
 935         Format specified values of `self` and return them.
 936 
 937         Parameters
 938         ----------
 939         slicer : int, array-like
 940             An indexer into `self` that specifies which values
 941             are used in the formatting process.
 942         kwargs : dict
 943             Options for specifying how the values should be formatted.
 944             These options include the following:
 945 
 946             1) na_rep : str
 947                 The value that serves as a placeholder for NULL values
 948             2) quoting : bool or None
 949                 Whether or not there are quoted values in `self`
 950             3) date_format : str
 951                 The format used to represent date-like values.
 952 
 953         Returns
 954         -------
 955         numpy.ndarray
 956             Formatted values.
 957         """
 958         values = self
 959         if slicer is not None:
 960             values = values[slicer]
 961         return values._format_native_types(**kwargs)
 962 
 963     def _format_native_types(self, na_rep="", quoting=None, **kwargs):
 964         """
 965         Actually format specific types of the index.
 966         """
 967         mask = isna(self)
 968         if not self.is_object() and not quoting:
 969             values = np.asarray(self).astype(str)
 970         else:
 971             values = np.array(self, dtype=object, copy=True)
 972 
 973         values[mask] = na_rep
 974         return values

 976     def _summary(self, name=None) -> str_t:
 977         """
 978         Return a summarized representation.
 979 
 980         Parameters
 981         ----------
 982         name : str
 983             name to use in the summary representation
 984 
 985         Returns
 986         -------
 987         String with a summarized representation of the index
 988         """
 989         if len(self) > 0:
 990             head = self[0]
 991             if hasattr(head, "format") and not isinstance(head, str):
 992                 head = head.format()
 993             tail = self[-1]
 994             if hasattr(tail, "format") and not isinstance(tail, str):
 995                 tail = tail.format()
 996             index_summary = f", {head} to {tail}"
 997         else:
 998             index_summary = ""
 999 
1000         if name is None:
1001             name = type(self).__name__
1002         return f"{name}: {len(self)} entries{index_summary}"

1027     def to_series(self, index=None, name=None):
1028         """
1029         Create a Series with both index and values equal to the index keys.
1030 
1031         Useful with map for returning an indexer based on an index.
1032 
1033         Parameters
1034         ----------
1035         index : Index, optional
1036             Index of resulting Series. If None, defaults to original index.
1037         name : str, optional
1038             Name of resulting Series. If None, defaults to name of original
1039             index.
1040 
1041         Returns
1042         -------
1043         Series
1044             The dtype will be based on the type of the Index values.
1045 
1046         See Also
1047         --------

1049         Series.to_frame : Convert Series to DataFrame.
1050 
1051         Examples
1052         --------

1054 
1055         By default, the original Index and original name is reused.
1056

1063 
1064         To enforce a new Index, specify new labels to ``index``:
1065

1073 
1074         >>> idx.to_series(name='zoo')
1075         animal
1076         Ant      Ant
1077         Bear    Bear
1078         Cow      Cow
1079         Name: zoo, dtype: object
1080         """
1081         from pandas import Series
1082 
1083         if index is None:
1084             index = self._shallow_copy()
1085         if name is None:
1086             name = self.name
1087 
1088         return Series(self.values.copy(), index=index, name=name)

1090     def to_frame(self, index: bool = True, name=None):
1091         """

1093 
1094         .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
1095 
1096         Parameters
1097         ----------
1098         index : bool, default True
1099             Set the index of the returned DataFrame as the original Index.

1101         name : object, default None

1116         --------

1119                animal
1120         animal
1121         Ant       Ant

1161     @name.setter

1163         if self._no_setting_name:
1164             # Used in MultiIndex.levels to avoid silently ignoring name updates.
1165             raise RuntimeError(
1166                 "Cannot set name on a level of a MultiIndex. Use "
1167                 "'MultiIndex.set_names' instead."
1168             )

1172     def _validate_names(self, name=None, names=None, deep: bool = False):
1173         """
1174         Handles the quirks of having a singular 'name' parameter for general
1175         Index and plural 'names' parameter for MultiIndex.
1176         """
1177         from copy import deepcopy
1178 
1179         if names is not None and name is not None:
1180             raise TypeError("Can only provide one of `names` and `name`")
1181         elif names is None and name is None:
1182             return deepcopy(self.names) if deep else self.names
1183         elif names is not None:
1184             if not is_list_like(names):
1185                 raise TypeError("Must pass list-like as `names`.")
1186             return names
1187         else:
1188             if not is_list_like(name):
1189                 return [name]
1190             return name
1191 
1192     def _get_names(self):
1193         return FrozenList((self.name,))
1194 
1195     def _set_names(self, values, level=None):
1196         """
1197         Set new names on index. Each name has to be a hashable type.
1198 
1199         Parameters
1200         ----------
1201         values : str or sequence
1202             name(s) to set
1203         level : int, level name, or sequence of int/level names (default None)
1204             If the index is a MultiIndex (hierarchical), level(s) to set (None
1205             for all levels).  Otherwise level must be None
1206 
1207         Raises
1208         ------
1209         TypeError if each name is not hashable.
1210         """
1211         if not is_list_like(values):
1212             raise ValueError("Names must be a list-like")
1213         if len(values) != 1:
1214             raise ValueError(f"Length of new names must be 1, got {len(values)}")
1215 
1216         # GH 20527
1217         # All items in 'name' need to be hashable:
1218         for name in values:
1219             if not is_hashable(name):
1220                 raise TypeError(f"{type(self).__name__}.name must be a hashable type")
1221         self._name = values[0]
1222 
1223     names = property(fset=_set_names, fget=_get_names)

1225     def set_names(self, names, level=None, inplace: bool = False):
1226         """
1227         Set Index or MultiIndex name.
1228 
1229         Able to set new names partially and by level.
1230 
1231         Parameters
1232         ----------
1233         names : label or list of label
1234             Name(s) to set.
1235         level : int, label or list of int or label, optional
1236             If the index is a MultiIndex, level(s) to set (None for all
1237             levels). Otherwise level must be None.
1238         inplace : bool, default False
1239             Modifies the object directly, instead of creating a new Index or
1240             MultiIndex.
1241 
1242         Returns
1243         -------
1244         Index
1245             The same type as the caller or None if inplace is True.
1246 
1247         See Also
1248         --------
1249         Index.rename : Able to set new names without level.
1250 
1251         Examples
1252         --------
1253         >>> idx = pd.Index([1, 2, 3, 4])
1254         >>> idx
1255         Int64Index([1, 2, 3, 4], dtype='int64')
1256         >>> idx.set_names('quarter')
1257         Int64Index([1, 2, 3, 4], dtype='int64', name='quarter')
1258 
1259         >>> idx = pd.MultiIndex.from_product([['python', 'cobra'],
1260         ...                                   [2018, 2019]])
1261         >>> idx
1262         MultiIndex([('python', 2018),
1263                     ('python', 2019),
1264                     ( 'cobra', 2018),
1265                     ( 'cobra', 2019)],
1266                    )
1267         >>> idx.set_names(['kind', 'year'], inplace=True)
1268         >>> idx
1269         MultiIndex([('python', 2018),
1270                     ('python', 2019),
1271                     ( 'cobra', 2018),
1272                     ( 'cobra', 2019)],
1273                    names=['kind', 'year'])
1274         >>> idx.set_names('species', level=0)
1275         MultiIndex([('python', 2018),
1276                     ('python', 2019),
1277                     ( 'cobra', 2018),
1278                     ( 'cobra', 2019)],
1279                    names=['species', 'year'])
1280         """
1281         if level is not None and not isinstance(self, ABCMultiIndex):
1282             raise ValueError("Level must be None for non-MultiIndex")
1283 
1284         if level is not None and not is_list_like(level) and is_list_like(names):
1285             raise TypeError("Names must be a string when a single level is provided.")
1286 
1287         if not is_list_like(names) and level is None and self.nlevels > 1:
1288             raise TypeError("Must pass list-like as `names`.")
1289 
1290         if not is_list_like(names):
1291             names = [names]
1292         if level is not None and not is_list_like(level):
1293             level = [level]
1294 
1295         if inplace:
1296             idx = self
1297         else:
1298             idx = self._shallow_copy()
1299         idx._set_names(names, level=level)
1300         if not inplace:
1301             return idx
1302 
1303     def rename(self, name, inplace=False):
1304         """
1305         Alter Index or MultiIndex name.
1306 
1307         Able to set new names without level. Defaults to returning new index.
1308         Length of names must match number of levels in MultiIndex.
1309 
1310         Parameters
1311         ----------
1312         name : label or list of labels
1313             Name(s) to set.
1314         inplace : bool, default False
1315             Modifies the object directly, instead of creating a new Index or
1316             MultiIndex.
1317 
1318         Returns
1319         -------
1320         Index
1321             The same type as the caller or None if inplace is True.
1322 
1323         See Also
1324         --------
1325         Index.set_names : Able to set new names partially and by level.
1326 
1327         Examples
1328         --------
1329         >>> idx = pd.Index(['A', 'C', 'A', 'B'], name='score')
1330         >>> idx.rename('grade')
1331         Index(['A', 'C', 'A', 'B'], dtype='object', name='grade')
1332 
1333         >>> idx = pd.MultiIndex.from_product([['python', 'cobra'],
1334         ...                                   [2018, 2019]],
1335         ...                                   names=['kind', 'year'])
1336         >>> idx
1337         MultiIndex([('python', 2018),
1338                     ('python', 2019),
1339                     ( 'cobra', 2018),
1340                     ( 'cobra', 2019)],
1341                    names=['kind', 'year'])
1342         >>> idx.rename(['species', 'year'])
1343         MultiIndex([('python', 2018),
1344                     ('python', 2019),
1345                     ( 'cobra', 2018),
1346                     ( 'cobra', 2019)],
1347                    names=['species', 'year'])
1348         >>> idx.rename('species')
1349         Traceback (most recent call last):
1350         TypeError: Must pass list-like as `names`.
1351         """
1352         return self.set_names([name], inplace=inplace)

1370     def _validate_index_level(self, level):
1371         """
1372         Validate index level.
1373 
1374         For single-level Index getting level number is a no-op, but some
1375         verification must be done like in MultiIndex.
1376 
1377         """
1378         if isinstance(level, int):
1379             if level < 0 and level != -1:
1380                 raise IndexError(
1381                     "Too many levels: Index has only 1 level, "
1382                     f"{level} is not a valid level number"
1383                 )
1384             elif level > 0:
1385                 raise IndexError(
1386                     f"Too many levels: Index has only 1 level, not {level + 1}"
1387                 )
1388         elif level != self.name:
1389             raise KeyError(
1390                 f"Requested level ({level}) does not match index name ({self.name})"
1391             )
1392 
1393     def _get_level_number(self, level) -> int:
1394         self._validate_index_level(level)
1395         return 0
1396 
1397     def sortlevel(self, level=None, ascending=True, sort_remaining=None):
1398         """
1399         For internal compatibility with with the Index API.
1400 
1401         Sort the Index. This is for compat with MultiIndex
1402 
1403         Parameters
1404         ----------
1405         ascending : bool, default True
1406             False to sort in descending order
1407 
1408         level, sort_remaining are compat parameters
1409 
1410         Returns
1411         -------
1412         Index
1413         """
1414         return self.sort_values(return_indexer=True, ascending=ascending)

1416     def _get_level_values(self, level):
1417         """
1418         Return an Index of values for requested level.
1419 
1420         This is primarily useful to get an individual level of values from a
1421         MultiIndex, but is provided on Index as well for compatibility.
1422 
1423         Parameters
1424         ----------
1425         level : int or str
1426             It is either the integer position or the name of the level.
1427 
1428         Returns
1429         -------
1430         Index
1431             Calling object, as there is only one level in the Index.
1432 
1433         See Also
1434         --------
1435         MultiIndex.get_level_values : Get values for a level of a MultiIndex.
1436 
1437         Notes
1438         -----
1439         For Index, level should be 0, since there are no multiple levels.
1440 
1441         Examples
1442         --------
1443         >>> idx = pd.Index(list('abc'))
1444         >>> idx
1445         Index(['a', 'b', 'c'], dtype='object')
1446 
1447         Get level values by supplying `level` as integer:
1448 
1449         >>> idx.get_level_values(0)
1450         Index(['a', 'b', 'c'], dtype='object')
1451         """
1452         self._validate_index_level(level)
1453         return self
1454 
1455     get_level_values = _get_level_values

1457     def droplevel(self, level=0):
1458         """
1459         Return index with requested level(s) removed.
1460 
1461         If resulting index has only 1 level left, the result will be
1462         of Index type, not MultiIndex.
1463 
1464         .. versionadded:: 0.23.1 (support for non-MultiIndex)
1465 
1466         Parameters
1467         ----------
1468         level : int, str, or list-like, default 0
1469             If a string is given, must be the name of a level
1470             If list-like, elements must be names or indexes of levels.
1471 
1472         Returns
1473         -------
1474         Index or MultiIndex
1475         """
1476         if not isinstance(level, (tuple, list)):
1477             level = [level]
1478 
1479         levnums = sorted(self._get_level_number(lev) for lev in level)[::-1]
1480 
1481         if len(level) == 0:
1482             return self
1483         if len(level) >= self.nlevels:
1484             raise ValueError(
1485                 f"Cannot remove {len(level)} levels from an index with {self.nlevels} "
1486                 "levels: at least one level must be left."
1487             )
1488         # The two checks above guarantee that here self is a MultiIndex
1489 
1490         new_levels = list(self.levels)
1491         new_codes = list(self.codes)
1492         new_names = list(self.names)
1493 
1494         for i in levnums:
1495             new_levels.pop(i)
1496             new_codes.pop(i)
1497             new_names.pop(i)
1498 
1499         if len(new_levels) == 1:
1500 
1501             # set nan if needed
1502             mask = new_codes[0] == -1
1503             result = new_levels[0].take(new_codes[0])
1504             if mask.any():
1505                 result = result.putmask(mask, np.nan)
1506 
1507             result._name = new_names[0]
1508             return result
1509         else:
1510             from pandas.core.indexes.multi import MultiIndex
1511 
1512             return MultiIndex(
1513                 levels=new_levels,
1514                 codes=new_codes,
1515                 names=new_names,
1516                 verify_integrity=False,
1517             )
1518 
1519     def _get_grouper_for_level(self, mapper, level=None):
1520         """
1521         Get index grouper corresponding to an index level
1522 
1523         Parameters
1524         ----------
1525         mapper: Group mapping function or None
1526             Function mapping index values to groups
1527         level : int or None
1528             Index level
1529 
1530         Returns
1531         -------
1532         grouper : Index
1533             Index of values to group on.
1534         labels : ndarray of int or None
1535             Array of locations in level_index.
1536         uniques : Index or None
1537             Index of unique values for level.
1538         """
1539         assert level is None or level == 0
1540         if mapper is None:
1541             grouper = self
1542         else:
1543             grouper = self.map(mapper)
1544 
1545         return grouper, None, None

2007     @cache_readonly
2008     def _isnan(self):
2009         """
2010         Return if each value is NaN.
2011         """
2012         if self._can_hold_na:
2013             return isna(self)
2014         else:
2015             # shouldn't reach to this condition by checking hasnans beforehand
2016             values = np.empty(len(self), dtype=np.bool_)
2017             values.fill(False)
2018             return values

2022         if self._can_hold_na:
2023             return self._isnan.nonzero()[0]
2024         else:
2025             return np.array([], dtype=np.int64)

2027     @cache_readonly
2028     def hasnans(self) -> bool:
2029         """
2030         Return if I have any nans; enables various perf speedups.
2031         """
2032         if self._can_hold_na:
2033             return bool(self._isnan.any())
2034         else:

2037     def isna(self):
2038         """
2039         Detect missing values.
2040 
2041         Return a boolean same-sized object indicating if the values are NA.
2042         NA values, such as ``None``, :attr:`numpy.NaN` or :attr:`pd.NaT`, get
2043         mapped to ``True`` values.
2044         Everything else get mapped to ``False`` values. Characters such as
2045         empty strings `''` or :attr:`numpy.inf` are not considered NA values
2046         (unless you set ``pandas.options.mode.use_inf_as_na = True``).
2047 
2048         Returns
2049         -------
2050         numpy.ndarray
2051             A boolean array of whether my values are NA.
2052 
2053         See Also
2054         --------
2055         Index.notna : Boolean inverse of isna.
2056         Index.dropna : Omit entries with missing values.
2057         isna : Top-level isna.
2058         Series.isna : Detect missing values in Series object.
2059 
2060         Examples
2061         --------
2062         Show which entries in a pandas.Index are NA. The result is an
2063         array.
2064 
2065         >>> idx = pd.Index([5.2, 6.0, np.NaN])
2066         >>> idx
2067         Float64Index([5.2, 6.0, nan], dtype='float64')
2068         >>> idx.isna()
2069         array([False, False,  True])
2070 
2071         Empty strings are not considered NA values. None is considered an NA
2072         value.
2073 
2074         >>> idx = pd.Index(['black', '', 'red', None])
2075         >>> idx
2076         Index(['black', '', 'red', None], dtype='object')
2077         >>> idx.isna()
2078         array([False, False, False,  True])
2079 
2080         For datetimes, `NaT` (Not a Time) is considered as an NA value.
2081 
2082         >>> idx = pd.DatetimeIndex([pd.Timestamp('1940-04-25'),
2083         ...                         pd.Timestamp(''), None, pd.NaT])
2084         >>> idx
2085         DatetimeIndex(['1940-04-25', 'NaT', 'NaT', 'NaT'],
2086                       dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq=None)
2087         >>> idx.isna()
2088         array([False,  True,  True,  True])
2089         """
2090         return self._isnan
2091

2094     def notna(self):
2095         """
2096         Detect existing (non-missing) values.
2097 
2098         Return a boolean same-sized object indicating if the values are not NA.
2099         Non-missing values get mapped to ``True``. Characters such as empty
2100         strings ``''`` or :attr:`numpy.inf` are not considered NA values
2101         (unless you set ``pandas.options.mode.use_inf_as_na = True``).
2102         NA values, such as None or :attr:`numpy.NaN`, get mapped to ``False``
2103         values.
2104 
2105         Returns
2106         -------
2107         numpy.ndarray
2108             Boolean array to indicate which entries are not NA.
2109 
2110         See Also
2111         --------
2112         Index.notnull : Alias of notna.
2113         Index.isna: Inverse of notna.
2114         notna : Top-level notna.
2115 
2116         Examples
2117         --------
2118         Show which entries in an Index are not NA. The result is an
2119         array.
2120 
2121         >>> idx = pd.Index([5.2, 6.0, np.NaN])
2122         >>> idx
2123         Float64Index([5.2, 6.0, nan], dtype='float64')
2124         >>> idx.notna()
2125         array([ True,  True, False])
2126 
2127         Empty strings are not considered NA values. None is considered a NA
2128         value.
2129 
2130         >>> idx = pd.Index(['black', '', 'red', None])
2131         >>> idx
2132         Index(['black', '', 'red', None], dtype='object')
2133         >>> idx.notna()
2134         array([ True,  True,  True, False])
2135         """
2136         return ~self.isna()

2140     def fillna(self, value=None, downcast=None):
2141         """
2142         Fill NA/NaN values with the specified value.
2143 
2144         Parameters
2145         ----------
2146         value : scalar
2147             Scalar value to use to fill holes (e.g. 0).
2148             This value cannot be a list-likes.
2149         downcast : dict, default is None
2150             A dict of item->dtype of what to downcast if possible,
2151             or the string 'infer' which will try to downcast to an appropriate
2152             equal type (e.g. float64 to int64 if possible).
2153 
2154         Returns
2155         -------
2156         Index
2157 
2158         See Also
2159         --------
2160         DataFrame.fillna : Fill NaN values of a DataFrame.
2161         Series.fillna : Fill NaN Values of a Series.
2162         """
2163         self._assert_can_do_op(value)
2164         if self.hasnans:
2165             result = self.putmask(self._isnan, value)
2166             if downcast is None:
2167                 # no need to care metadata other than name
2168                 # because it can't have freq if
2169                 return Index(result, name=self.name)
2170         return self._shallow_copy()

2172     def dropna(self, how="any"):
2173         """
2174         Return Index without NA/NaN values.
2175 
2176         Parameters
2177         ----------
2178         how : {'any', 'all'}, default 'any'
2179             If the Index is a MultiIndex, drop the value when any or all levels
2180             are NaN.
2181 
2182         Returns
2183         -------
2184         Index
2185         """
2186         if how not in ("any", "all"):
2187             raise ValueError(f"invalid how option: {how}")
2188 
2189         if self.hasnans:
2190             return self._shallow_copy(self._values[~self._isnan])
2191         return self._shallow_copy()

2223     def drop_duplicates(self, keep="first"):

2271     def duplicated(self, keep="first"):
2272         """
2273         Indicate duplicate index values.
2274 
2275         Duplicated values are indicated as ``True`` values in the resulting
2276         array. Either all duplicates, all except the first, or all except the
2277         last occurrence of duplicates can be indicated.
2278 
2279         Parameters
2280         ----------
2281         keep : {'first', 'last', False}, default 'first'
2282             The value or values in a set of duplicates to mark as missing.
2283 
2284             - 'first' : Mark duplicates as ``True`` except for the first
2285               occurrence.
2286             - 'last' : Mark duplicates as ``True`` except for the last
2287               occurrence.
2288             - ``False`` : Mark all duplicates as ``True``.
2289 
2290         Returns
2291         -------
2292         numpy.ndarray
2293 
2294         See Also
2295         --------
2296         Series.duplicated : Equivalent method on pandas.Series.
2297         DataFrame.duplicated : Equivalent method on pandas.DataFrame.
2298         Index.drop_duplicates : Remove duplicate values from Index.
2299 
2300         Examples
2301         --------
2302         By default, for each set of duplicated values, the first occurrence is
2303         set to False and all others to True:
2304 
2305         >>> idx = pd.Index(['lama', 'cow', 'lama', 'beetle', 'lama'])
2306         >>> idx.duplicated()
2307         array([False, False,  True, False,  True])
2308 
2309         which is equivalent to
2310 
2311         >>> idx.duplicated(keep='first')
2312         array([False, False,  True, False,  True])
2313 
2314         By using 'last', the last occurrence of each set of duplicated values
2315         is set on False and all others on True:
2316 
2317         >>> idx.duplicated(keep='last')
2318         array([ True, False,  True, False, False])
2319 
2320         By setting keep on ``False``, all duplicates are True:
2321 
2322         >>> idx.duplicated(keep=False)
2323         array([ True, False,  True, False,  True])
2324         """
2325         return super().duplicated(keep=keep)

2327     def _get_unique_index(self, dropna: bool = False):
2328         """
2329         Returns an index containing unique values.
2330 
2331         Parameters
2332         ----------
2333         dropna : bool, default False
2334             If True, NaN values are dropped.
2335 
2336         Returns
2337         -------
2338         uniques : index
2339         """
2340         if self.is_unique and not dropna:
2341             return self
2342 
2343         if not self.is_unique:
2344             values = self.unique()
2345             if not isinstance(self, ABCMultiIndex):
2346                 # extract an array to pass to _shallow_copy
2347                 values = values._data
2348         else:
2349             values = self._values
2350 
2351         if dropna:
2352             try:
2353                 if self.hasnans:
2354                     values = values[~isna(values)]
2355             except NotImplementedError:
2356                 pass
2357 
2358         return self._shallow_copy(values)

2408     def _get_reconciled_name_object(self, other):
2409         """

2411         return self, unless the name changes, in which
2412         case make a shallow copy of self.

2419     def _union_incompatible_dtypes(self, other, sort):
2420         """
2421         Casts this and other index to object dtype to allow the formation
2422         of a union between incompatible types.
2423 
2424         Parameters
2425         ----------
2426         other : Index or array-like
2427         sort : False or None, default False
2428             Whether to sort the resulting index.
2429 
2430             * False : do not sort the result.
2431             * None : sort the result, except when `self` and `other` are equal
2432               or when the values cannot be compared.
2433 
2434         Returns
2435         -------
2436         Index
2437         """
2438         this = self.astype(object, copy=False)
2439         # cast to Index for when `other` is list-like
2440         other = Index(other).astype(object, copy=False)
2441         return Index.union(this, other, sort=sort).astype(object, copy=False)

2443     def _is_compatible_with_other(self, other) -> bool:
2444         """
2445         Check whether this and the other dtype are compatible with each other.
2446         Meaning a union can be formed between them without needing to be cast
2447         to dtype object.

2449         Parameters
2450         ----------
2451         other : Index or array-like
2452 
2453         Returns
2454         -------
2455         bool
2456         """
2457         return type(self) is type(other) and is_dtype_equal(self.dtype, other.dtype)

2466     def union(self, other, sort=None):
2467         """
2468         Form the union of two Index objects.
2469 
2470         If the Index objects are incompatible, both Index objects will be
2471         cast to dtype('object') first.
2472 
2473             .. versionchanged:: 0.25.0
2474 
2475         Parameters
2476         ----------
2477         other : Index or array-like
2478         sort : bool or None, default None
2479             Whether to sort the resulting Index.
2480 
2481             * None : Sort the result, except when
2482 
2483               1. `self` and `other` are equal.
2484               2. `self` or `other` has length 0.
2485               3. Some values in `self` or `other` cannot be compared.
2486                  A RuntimeWarning is issued in this case.
2487 
2488             * False : do not sort the result.
2489 
2490             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
2491 
2492             .. versionchanged:: 0.24.1
2493 
2494                Changed the default value from ``True`` to ``None``
2495                (without change in behaviour).
2496 
2497         Returns
2498         -------
2499         union : Index
2500 
2501         Examples
2502         --------
2503         Union matching dtypes
2504 
2505         >>> idx1 = pd.Index([1, 2, 3, 4])
2506         >>> idx2 = pd.Index([3, 4, 5, 6])
2507         >>> idx1.union(idx2)
2508         Int64Index([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6], dtype='int64')
2509 
2510         Union mismatched dtypes
2511 
2512         >>> idx1 = pd.Index(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd'])
2513         >>> idx2 = pd.Index([1, 2, 3, 4])
2514         >>> idx1.union(idx2)
2515         Index(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 1, 2, 3, 4], dtype='object')
2516         """
2517         self._validate_sort_keyword(sort)
2518         self._assert_can_do_setop(other)
2519 
2520         if not self._is_compatible_with_other(other):
2521             return self._union_incompatible_dtypes(other, sort=sort)
2522 
2523         return self._union(other, sort=sort)
2524 
2525     def _union(self, other, sort):
2526         """
2527         Specific union logic should go here. In subclasses, union behavior
2528         should be overwritten here rather than in `self.union`.
2529 
2530         Parameters
2531         ----------
2532         other : Index or array-like
2533         sort : False or None, default False
2534             Whether to sort the resulting index.
2535 
2536             * False : do not sort the result.
2537             * None : sort the result, except when `self` and `other` are equal
2538               or when the values cannot be compared.
2539 
2540         Returns
2541         -------
2542         Index
2543         """
2544         if not len(other) or self.equals(other):
2545             return self._get_reconciled_name_object(other)
2546 
2547         if not len(self):
2548             return other._get_reconciled_name_object(self)
2549 
2550         # TODO(EA): setops-refactor, clean all this up
2551         lvals = self._values
2552         rvals = other._values
2553 
2554         if sort is None and self.is_monotonic and other.is_monotonic:
2555             try:
2556                 result = self._outer_indexer(lvals, rvals)[0]
2557             except TypeError:
2558                 # incomparable objects
2559                 result = list(lvals)
2560 
2561                 # worth making this faster? a very unusual case
2562                 value_set = set(lvals)
2563                 result.extend([x for x in rvals if x not in value_set])
2564                 result = Index(result)._values  # do type inference here
2565         else:
2566             # find indexes of things in "other" that are not in "self"
2567             if self.is_unique:
2568                 indexer = self.get_indexer(other)
2569                 indexer = (indexer == -1).nonzero()[0]
2570             else:
2571                 indexer = algos.unique1d(self.get_indexer_non_unique(other)[1])
2572 
2573             if len(indexer) > 0:
2574                 other_diff = algos.take_nd(rvals, indexer, allow_fill=False)
2575                 result = concat_compat((lvals, other_diff))
2576 
2577             else:
2578                 result = lvals
2579 
2580             if sort is None:
2581                 try:
2582                     result = algos.safe_sort(result)
2583                 except TypeError as err:
2584                     warnings.warn(
2585                         f"{err}, sort order is undefined for incomparable objects",
2586                         RuntimeWarning,
2587                         stacklevel=3,
2588                     )
2589 
2590         # for subclasses
2591         return self._wrap_setop_result(other, result)
2592 
2593     def _wrap_setop_result(self, other, result):
2594         name = get_op_result_name(self, other)
2595         return self._shallow_copy(result, name=name)

2597     # TODO: standardize return type of non-union setops type(self vs other)
2598     def intersection(self, other, sort=False):
2599         """
2600         Form the intersection of two Index objects.
2601 
2602         This returns a new Index with elements common to the index and `other`.
2603 
2604         Parameters
2605         ----------
2606         other : Index or array-like
2607         sort : False or None, default False
2608             Whether to sort the resulting index.
2609 
2610             * False : do not sort the result.
2611             * None : sort the result, except when `self` and `other` are equal
2612               or when the values cannot be compared.
2613 
2614             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
2615 
2616             .. versionchanged:: 0.24.1
2617 
2618                Changed the default from ``True`` to ``False``, to match
2619                the behaviour of 0.23.4 and earlier.
2620 
2621         Returns
2622         -------
2623         intersection : Index
2624 
2625         Examples
2626         --------
2627         >>> idx1 = pd.Index([1, 2, 3, 4])
2628         >>> idx2 = pd.Index([3, 4, 5, 6])
2629         >>> idx1.intersection(idx2)
2630         Int64Index([3, 4], dtype='int64')
2631         """
2632         self._validate_sort_keyword(sort)
2633         self._assert_can_do_setop(other)
2634         other = ensure_index(other)
2635 
2636         if self.equals(other):
2637             return self._get_reconciled_name_object(other)
2638 
2639         if not is_dtype_equal(self.dtype, other.dtype):
2640             this = self.astype("O")
2641             other = other.astype("O")
2642             return this.intersection(other, sort=sort)
2643 
2644         # TODO(EA): setops-refactor, clean all this up
2645         lvals = self._values
2646         rvals = other._values
2647 
2648         if self.is_monotonic and other.is_monotonic:
2649             try:
2650                 result = self._inner_indexer(lvals, rvals)[0]
2651             except TypeError:
2652                 pass
2653             else:
2654                 return self._wrap_setop_result(other, result)
2655 
2656         try:
2657             indexer = Index(rvals).get_indexer(lvals)
2658             indexer = indexer.take((indexer != -1).nonzero()[0])
2659         except (InvalidIndexError, IncompatibleFrequency):
2660             # InvalidIndexError raised by get_indexer if non-unique
2661             # IncompatibleFrequency raised by PeriodIndex.get_indexer
2662             indexer = algos.unique1d(Index(rvals).get_indexer_non_unique(lvals)[0])
2663             indexer = indexer[indexer != -1]
2664 
2665         taken = other.take(indexer)
2666         res_name = get_op_result_name(self, other)
2667 
2668         if sort is None:
2669             taken = algos.safe_sort(taken.values)
2670             return self._shallow_copy(taken, name=res_name)
2671 
2672         taken.name = res_name
2673         return taken

2675     def difference(self, other, sort=None):
2676         """
2677         Return a new Index with elements of index not in `other`.
2678 
2679         This is the set difference of two Index objects.

2681         Parameters

2690               from comparing incomparable elements.
2691             * False : Do not sort the result.
2692 
2693             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
2694 
2695             .. versionchanged:: 0.24.1
2696

2698                (without change in behaviour).
2699 
2700         Returns
2701         -------
2702         difference : Index
2703 
2704         Examples
2705         --------
2706         >>> idx1 = pd.Index([2, 1, 3, 4])
2707         >>> idx2 = pd.Index([3, 4, 5, 6])
2708         >>> idx1.difference(idx2)
2709         Int64Index([1, 2], dtype='int64')
2710         >>> idx1.difference(idx2, sort=False)
2711         Int64Index([2, 1], dtype='int64')
2712         """
2713         self._validate_sort_keyword(sort)
2714         self._assert_can_do_setop(other)
2715 
2716         if self.equals(other):
2717             # pass an empty np.ndarray with the appropriate dtype
2718             return self._shallow_copy(self._data[:0])
2719 
2720         other, result_name = self._convert_can_do_setop(other)
2721 
2722         this = self._get_unique_index()
2723 
2724         indexer = this.get_indexer(other)
2725         indexer = indexer.take((indexer != -1).nonzero()[0])
2726 
2727         label_diff = np.setdiff1d(np.arange(this.size), indexer, assume_unique=True)
2728         the_diff = this.values.take(label_diff)
2729         if sort is None:
2730             try:
2731                 the_diff = algos.safe_sort(the_diff)
2732             except TypeError:
2733                 pass
2734 
2735         return this._shallow_copy(the_diff, name=result_name)
2736 
2737     def symmetric_difference(self, other, result_name=None, sort=None):
2738         """
2739         Compute the symmetric difference of two Index objects.
2740 
2741         Parameters
2742         ----------
2743         other : Index or array-like
2744         result_name : str
2745         sort : False or None, default None
2746             Whether to sort the resulting index. By default, the
2747             values are attempted to be sorted, but any TypeError from
2748             incomparable elements is caught by pandas.
2749 
2750             * None : Attempt to sort the result, but catch any TypeErrors
2751               from comparing incomparable elements.
2752             * False : Do not sort the result.
2753 
2754             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
2755 
2756             .. versionchanged:: 0.24.1
2757 
2758                Changed the default value from ``True`` to ``None``
2759                (without change in behaviour).
2760 
2761         Returns
2762         -------
2763         symmetric_difference : Index
2764 
2765         Notes
2766         -----
2767         ``symmetric_difference`` contains elements that appear in either
2768         ``idx1`` or ``idx2`` but not both. Equivalent to the Index created by
2769         ``idx1.difference(idx2) | idx2.difference(idx1)`` with duplicates
2770         dropped.
2771 
2772         Examples
2773         --------
2774         >>> idx1 = pd.Index([1, 2, 3, 4])
2775         >>> idx2 = pd.Index([2, 3, 4, 5])
2776         >>> idx1.symmetric_difference(idx2)
2777         Int64Index([1, 5], dtype='int64')
2778 
2779         You can also use the ``^`` operator:
2780 
2781         >>> idx1 ^ idx2
2782         Int64Index([1, 5], dtype='int64')
2783         """
2784         self._validate_sort_keyword(sort)
2785         self._assert_can_do_setop(other)
2786         other, result_name_update = self._convert_can_do_setop(other)
2787         if result_name is None:
2788             result_name = result_name_update
2789 
2790         this = self._get_unique_index()
2791         other = other._get_unique_index()
2792         indexer = this.get_indexer(other)
2793 
2794         # {this} minus {other}
2795         common_indexer = indexer.take((indexer != -1).nonzero()[0])
2796         left_indexer = np.setdiff1d(
2797             np.arange(this.size), common_indexer, assume_unique=True
2798         )
2799         left_diff = this._values.take(left_indexer)
2800 
2801         # {other} minus {this}
2802         right_indexer = (indexer == -1).nonzero()[0]
2803         right_diff = other._values.take(right_indexer)
2804 
2805         the_diff = concat_compat([left_diff, right_diff])
2806         if sort is None:
2807             try:
2808                 the_diff = algos.safe_sort(the_diff)
2809             except TypeError:
2810                 pass
2811 
2812         return Index(the_diff, dtype=self.dtype, name=result_name)
2813 
2814     def _assert_can_do_setop(self, other):
2815         if not is_list_like(other):
2816             raise TypeError("Input must be Index or array-like")
2817         return True
2818 
2819     def _convert_can_do_setop(self, other):
2820         if not isinstance(other, Index):
2821             other = Index(other, name=self.name)
2822             result_name = self.name
2823         else:
2824             result_name = get_op_result_name(self, other)
2825         return other, result_name

2830     def get_loc(self, key, method=None, tolerance=None):
2831         """
2832         Get integer location, slice or boolean mask for requested label.
2833 
2834         Parameters
2835         ----------
2836         key : label
2837         method : {None, 'pad'/'ffill', 'backfill'/'bfill', 'nearest'}, optional
2838             * default: exact matches only.
2839             * pad / ffill: find the PREVIOUS index value if no exact match.
2840             * backfill / bfill: use NEXT index value if no exact match
2841             * nearest: use the NEAREST index value if no exact match. Tied
2842               distances are broken by preferring the larger index value.
2843         tolerance : int or float, optional
2844             Maximum distance from index value for inexact matches. The value of
2845             the index at the matching location most satisfy the equation
2846             ``abs(index[loc] - key) <= tolerance``.
2847 
2848         Returns
2849         -------
2850         loc : int if unique index, slice if monotonic index, else mask
2851 
2852         Examples
2853         --------
2854         >>> unique_index = pd.Index(list('abc'))
2855         >>> unique_index.get_loc('b')
2856         1
2857 
2858         >>> monotonic_index = pd.Index(list('abbc'))
2859         >>> monotonic_index.get_loc('b')
2860         slice(1, 3, None)
2861 
2862         >>> non_monotonic_index = pd.Index(list('abcb'))
2863         >>> non_monotonic_index.get_loc('b')
2864         array([False,  True, False,  True])
2865         """
2866         if method is None:
2867             if tolerance is not None:
2868                 raise ValueError(
2869                     "tolerance argument only valid if using pad, "
2870                     "backfill or nearest lookups"
2871                 )
2872             casted_key = self._maybe_cast_indexer(key)
2873             try:
2874                 return self._engine.get_loc(casted_key)
2875             except KeyError as err:
2876                 raise KeyError(key) from err
2877 
2878         if tolerance is not None:
2879             tolerance = self._convert_tolerance(tolerance, np.asarray(key))
2880 
2881         indexer = self.get_indexer([key], method=method, tolerance=tolerance)
2882         if indexer.ndim > 1 or indexer.size > 1:
2883             raise TypeError("get_loc requires scalar valued input")
2884         loc = indexer.item()
2885         if loc == -1:
2886             raise KeyError(key)
2887         return loc

2933         and ``x`` is marked by -1, as it is not in ``index``.

2936     @Appender(_index_shared_docs["get_indexer"] % _index_doc_kwargs)
2937     def get_indexer(
2938         self, target, method=None, limit=None, tolerance=None
2939     ) -> np.ndarray:
2940         method = missing.clean_reindex_fill_method(method)
2941         target = ensure_index(target)
2942         if tolerance is not None:
2943             tolerance = self._convert_tolerance(tolerance, target)
2944 
2945         # Treat boolean labels passed to a numeric index as not found. Without
2946         # this fix False and True would be treated as 0 and 1 respectively.
2947         # (GH #16877)
2948         if target.is_boolean() and self.is_numeric():
2949             return ensure_platform_int(np.repeat(-1, target.size))
2950 
2951         pself, ptarget = self._maybe_promote(target)
2952         if pself is not self or ptarget is not target:
2953             return pself.get_indexer(
2954                 ptarget, method=method, limit=limit, tolerance=tolerance
2955             )
2956 
2957         if not is_dtype_equal(self.dtype, target.dtype):
2958             this = self.astype(object)
2959             target = target.astype(object)
2960             return this.get_indexer(
2961                 target, method=method, limit=limit, tolerance=tolerance
2962             )
2963 
2964         if not self.is_unique:
2965             raise InvalidIndexError(
2966                 "Reindexing only valid with uniquely valued Index objects"
2967             )
2968 
2969         if method == "pad" or method == "backfill":
2970             indexer = self._get_fill_indexer(target, method, limit, tolerance)
2971         elif method == "nearest":
2972             indexer = self._get_nearest_indexer(target, limit, tolerance)
2973         else:
2974             if tolerance is not None:
2975                 raise ValueError(
2976                     "tolerance argument only valid if doing pad, "
2977                     "backfill or nearest reindexing"
2978                 )
2979             if limit is not None:
2980                 raise ValueError(
2981                     "limit argument only valid if doing pad, "
2982                     "backfill or nearest reindexing"
2983                 )
2984 
2985             indexer = self._engine.get_indexer(target._get_engine_target())
2986 
2987         return ensure_platform_int(indexer)

2996     def _get_fill_indexer(
2997         self, target: "Index", method: str_t, limit=None, tolerance=None
2998     ) -> np.ndarray:
2999 
3000         target_values = target._get_engine_target()

3015     def _get_fill_indexer_searchsorted(
3016         self, target: "Index", method: str_t, limit=None
3017     ) -> np.ndarray:
3018         """
3019         Fallback pad/backfill get_indexer that works for monotonic decreasing
3020         indexes and non-monotonic targets.
3021         """
3022         if limit is not None:
3023             raise ValueError(
3024                 f"limit argument for {repr(method)} method only well-defined "
3025                 "if index and target are monotonic"
3026             )
3027 
3028         side = "left" if method == "pad" else "right"
3029 
3030         # find exact matches first (this simplifies the algorithm)
3031         indexer = self.get_indexer(target)
3032         nonexact = indexer == -1
3033         indexer[nonexact] = self._searchsorted_monotonic(target[nonexact], side)
3034         if side == "left":
3035             # searchsorted returns "indices into a sorted array such that,
3036             # if the corresponding elements in v were inserted before the
3037             # indices, the order of a would be preserved".
3038             # Thus, we need to subtract 1 to find values to the left.
3039             indexer[nonexact] -= 1
3040             # This also mapped not found values (values of 0 from
3041             # np.searchsorted) to -1, which conveniently is also our
3042             # sentinel for missing values
3043         else:
3044             # Mark indices to the right of the largest value as not found
3045             indexer[indexer == len(self)] = -1
3046         return indexer

3048     def _get_nearest_indexer(self, target: "Index", limit, tolerance) -> np.ndarray:
3049         """
3050         Get the indexer for the nearest index labels; requires an index with
3051         values that can be subtracted from each other (e.g., not strings or
3052         tuples).
3053         """
3054         left_indexer = self.get_indexer(target, "pad", limit=limit)
3055         right_indexer = self.get_indexer(target, "backfill", limit=limit)
3056 
3057         target_values = target._values
3058         left_distances = np.abs(self._values[left_indexer] - target_values)
3059         right_distances = np.abs(self._values[right_indexer] - target_values)
3060 
3061         op = operator.lt if self.is_monotonic_increasing else operator.le
3062         indexer = np.where(
3063             op(left_distances, right_distances) | (right_indexer == -1),
3064             left_indexer,
3065             right_indexer,
3066         )
3067         if tolerance is not None:
3068             indexer = self._filter_indexer_tolerance(target_values, indexer, tolerance)
3069         return indexer

3071     def _filter_indexer_tolerance(
3072         self,
3073         target: Union["Index", np.ndarray, ExtensionArray],
3074         indexer: np.ndarray,
3075         tolerance,
3076     ) -> np.ndarray:
3077         distance = abs(self._values[indexer] - target)
3078         indexer = np.where(distance <= tolerance, indexer, -1)
3079         return indexer

3103     def _convert_slice_indexer(self, key: slice, kind: str_t):
3104         """
3105         Convert a slice indexer.
3106 
3107         By definition, these are labels unless 'iloc' is passed in.
3108         Floats are not allowed as the start, step, or stop of the slice.
3109 
3110         Parameters
3111         ----------
3112         key : label of the slice bound
3113         kind : {'loc', 'getitem'}
3114         """
3115         assert kind in ["loc", "getitem"], kind
3116 
3117         # potentially cast the bounds to integers
3118         start, stop, step = key.start, key.stop, key.step
3119 
3120         # figure out if this is a positional indexer
3121         def is_int(v):
3122             return v is None or is_integer(v)
3123 
3124         is_index_slice = is_int(start) and is_int(stop) and is_int(step)
3125         is_positional = is_index_slice and not (
3126             self.is_integer() or self.is_categorical()
3127         )
3128 
3129         if kind == "getitem":
3130             """
3131             called from the getitem slicers, validate that we are in fact
3132             integers
3133             """
3134             if self.is_integer() or is_index_slice:
3135                 self._validate_indexer("slice", key.start, "getitem")
3136                 self._validate_indexer("slice", key.stop, "getitem")
3137                 self._validate_indexer("slice", key.step, "getitem")
3138                 return key
3139 
3140         # convert the slice to an indexer here
3141 
3142         # if we are mixed and have integers
3143         if is_positional:
3144             try:
3145                 # Validate start & stop
3146                 if start is not None:
3147                     self.get_loc(start)
3148                 if stop is not None:
3149                     self.get_loc(stop)
3150                 is_positional = False
3151             except KeyError:
3152                 pass

3164                     FutureWarning,
