3270     def reindex(self, target, method=None, level=None, limit=None, tolerance=None):
3271         """
3272         Create index with target's values.
3273 
3274         Parameters
3275         ----------
3276         target : an iterable
3277 
3278         Returns
3279         -------
3280         new_index : pd.Index
3281             Resulting index.
3282         indexer : np.ndarray or None
3283             Indices of output values in original index.
3284         """
3285         # GH6552: preserve names when reindexing to non-named target
3286         # (i.e. neither Index nor Series).
3287         preserve_names = not hasattr(target, "name")
3288 
3289         # GH7774: preserve dtype/tz if target is empty and not an Index.
3290         target = ensure_has_len(target)  # target may be an iterator
3291 
3292         if not isinstance(target, Index) and len(target) == 0:
3293             if isinstance(self, ABCRangeIndex):
3294                 values = range(0)
3295             else:
3296                 values = self._data[:0]  # appropriately-dtyped empty array
3297             target = self._simple_new(values, name=self.name)
3298         else:
3299             target = ensure_index(target)
3300 
3301         if level is not None:
3302             if method is not None:
3303                 raise TypeError("Fill method not supported if level passed")
3304             _, indexer, _ = self._join_level(
3305                 target, level, how="right", return_indexers=True
3306             )
3307         else:
3308             if self.equals(target):
3309                 indexer = None
3310             else:
3311                 # check is_overlapping for IntervalIndex compat
3312                 if self.is_unique and not getattr(self, "is_overlapping", False):
3313                     indexer = self.get_indexer(
3314                         target, method=method, limit=limit, tolerance=tolerance
3315                     )
3316                 else:
3317                     if method is not None or limit is not None:
3318                         raise ValueError(
3319                             "cannot reindex a non-unique index "
3320                             "with a method or limit"
3321                         )
3322                     indexer, missing = self.get_indexer_non_unique(target)
3323 
3324         if preserve_names and target.nlevels == 1 and target.name != self.name:
3325             target = target.copy()
3326             target.name = self.name
3327 
3328         return target, indexer

3361 
3362             new_labels = np.empty(tuple([len(indexer)]), dtype=object)
3363             new_labels[cur_indexer] = cur_labels
3364             new_labels[missing_indexer] = missing_labels
3365 
3366             # a unique indexer
3367             if target.is_unique:
3368 
3369                 # see GH5553, make sure we use the right indexer
3370                 new_indexer = np.arange(len(indexer))
3371                 new_indexer[cur_indexer] = np.arange(len(cur_labels))
3372                 new_indexer[missing_indexer] = -1
3373 
3374             # we have a non_unique selector, need to use the original
3375             # indexer here
3376             else:
3377 
3378                 # need to retake to have the same size as the indexer
3379                 indexer[~check] = -1
3380 
3381                 # reset the new indexer to account for the new size
3382                 new_indexer = np.arange(len(self.take(indexer)))
3383                 new_indexer[~check] = -1
3384 
3385         new_index = Index(new_labels, name=self.name)
3386         return new_index, indexer, new_indexer

3391     def join(self, other, how="left", level=None, return_indexers=False, sort=False):
3392         """
3393         Compute join_index and indexers to conform data
3394         structures to the new index.
3395 
3396         Parameters
3397         ----------
3398         other : Index
3399         how : {'left', 'right', 'inner', 'outer'}
3400         level : int or level name, default None
3401         return_indexers : bool, default False
3402         sort : bool, default False
3403             Sort the join keys lexicographically in the result Index. If False,
3404             the order of the join keys depends on the join type (how keyword).
3405 
3406         Returns
3407         -------
3408         join_index, (left_indexer, right_indexer)
3409         """
3410         other = ensure_index(other)
3411         self_is_mi = isinstance(self, ABCMultiIndex)
3412         other_is_mi = isinstance(other, ABCMultiIndex)
3413 
3414         # try to figure out the join level
3415         # GH3662
3416         if level is None and (self_is_mi or other_is_mi):
3417 
3418             # have the same levels/names so a simple join
3419             if self.names == other.names:
3420                 pass
3421             else:
3422                 return self._join_multi(other, how=how, return_indexers=return_indexers)
3423 
3424         # join on the level
3425         if level is not None and (self_is_mi or other_is_mi):
3426             return self._join_level(
3427                 other, level, how=how, return_indexers=return_indexers
3428             )
3429 
3430         if len(other) == 0 and how in ("left", "outer"):
3431             join_index = self._shallow_copy()
3432             if return_indexers:
3433                 rindexer = np.repeat(-1, len(join_index))
3434                 return join_index, None, rindexer
3435             else:
3436                 return join_index
3437 
3438         if len(self) == 0 and how in ("right", "outer"):
3439             join_index = other._shallow_copy()
3440             if return_indexers:
3441                 lindexer = np.repeat(-1, len(join_index))
3442                 return join_index, lindexer, None
3443             else:
3444                 return join_index
3445 
3446         if self._join_precedence < other._join_precedence:
3447             how = {"right": "left", "left": "right"}.get(how, how)
3448             result = other.join(
3449                 self, how=how, level=level, return_indexers=return_indexers
3450             )
3451             if return_indexers:
3452                 x, y, z = result
3453                 result = x, z, y
3454             return result
3455 
3456         if not is_dtype_equal(self.dtype, other.dtype):
3457             this = self.astype("O")
3458             other = other.astype("O")
3459             return this.join(other, how=how, return_indexers=return_indexers)
3460 
3461         _validate_join_method(how)
3462 
3463         if not self.is_unique and not other.is_unique:
3464             return self._join_non_unique(
3465                 other, how=how, return_indexers=return_indexers
3466             )
3467         elif not self.is_unique or not other.is_unique:
3468             if self.is_monotonic and other.is_monotonic:
3469                 return self._join_monotonic(
3470                     other, how=how, return_indexers=return_indexers
3471                 )
3472             else:
3473                 return self._join_non_unique(
3474                     other, how=how, return_indexers=return_indexers
3475                 )
3476         elif self.is_monotonic and other.is_monotonic:
3477             try:
3478                 return self._join_monotonic(
3479                     other, how=how, return_indexers=return_indexers
3480                 )
3481             except TypeError:
3482                 pass
3483 
3484         if how == "left":
3485             join_index = self
3486         elif how == "right":
3487             join_index = other
3488         elif how == "inner":
3489             # TODO: sort=False here for backwards compat. It may
3490             # be better to use the sort parameter passed into join
3491             join_index = self.intersection(other, sort=False)
3492         elif how == "outer":
3493             # TODO: sort=True here for backwards compat. It may
3494             # be better to use the sort parameter passed into join
3495             join_index = self.union(other)
3496 
3497         if sort:
3498             join_index = join_index.sort_values()
3499 
3500         if return_indexers:
3501             if join_index is self:
3502                 lindexer = None
3503             else:
3504                 lindexer = self.get_indexer(join_index)
3505             if join_index is other:
3506                 rindexer = None
3507             else:
3508                 rindexer = other.get_indexer(join_index)
3509             return join_index, lindexer, rindexer
3510         else:
3511             return join_index
3512 
3513     def _join_multi(self, other, how, return_indexers=True):
3514         from pandas.core.indexes.multi import MultiIndex
3515         from pandas.core.reshape.merge import _restore_dropped_levels_multijoin
3516 
3517         # figure out join names
3518         self_names = set(com.not_none(*self.names))
3519         other_names = set(com.not_none(*other.names))
3520         overlap = self_names & other_names
3521 
3522         # need at least 1 in common
3523         if not overlap:
3524             raise ValueError("cannot join with no overlapping index names")
3525 
3526         self_is_mi = isinstance(self, ABCMultiIndex)
3527         other_is_mi = isinstance(other, ABCMultiIndex)
3528 
3529         if self_is_mi and other_is_mi:
3530 
3531             # Drop the non-matching levels from left and right respectively
3532             ldrop_names = list(self_names - overlap)
3533             rdrop_names = list(other_names - overlap)
3534 
3535             # if only the order differs
3536             if not len(ldrop_names + rdrop_names):
3537                 self_jnlevels = self
3538                 other_jnlevels = other.reorder_levels(self.names)
3539             else:
3540                 self_jnlevels = self.droplevel(ldrop_names)
3541                 other_jnlevels = other.droplevel(rdrop_names)
3542 
3543             # Join left and right
3544             # Join on same leveled multi-index frames is supported
3545             join_idx, lidx, ridx = self_jnlevels.join(
3546                 other_jnlevels, how, return_indexers=True
3547             )
3548 
3549             # Restore the dropped levels
3550             # Returned index level order is
3551             # common levels, ldrop_names, rdrop_names
3552             dropped_names = ldrop_names + rdrop_names
3553 
3554             levels, codes, names = _restore_dropped_levels_multijoin(
3555                 self, other, dropped_names, join_idx, lidx, ridx
3556             )
3557 
3558             # Re-create the multi-index
3559             multi_join_idx = MultiIndex(
3560                 levels=levels, codes=codes, names=names, verify_integrity=False
3561             )
3562 
3563             multi_join_idx = multi_join_idx.remove_unused_levels()
3564 
3565             if return_indexers:
3566                 return multi_join_idx, lidx, ridx
3567             else:
3568                 return multi_join_idx
3569 
3570         jl = list(overlap)[0]
3571 
3572         # Case where only one index is multi
3573         # make the indices into mi's that match
3574         flip_order = False
3575         if self_is_mi:
3576             self, other = other, self
3577             flip_order = True
3578             # flip if join method is right or left
3579             how = {"right": "left", "left": "right"}.get(how, how)
3580 
3581         level = other.names.index(jl)
3582         result = self._join_level(
3583             other, level, how=how, return_indexers=return_indexers
3584         )
3585 
3586         if flip_order:
3587             if isinstance(result, tuple):
3588                 return result[0], result[2], result[1]
3589         return result
3590 
3591     def _join_non_unique(self, other, how="left", return_indexers=False):
3592         from pandas.core.reshape.merge import _get_join_indexers
3593 
3594         # We only get here if dtypes match
3595         assert self.dtype == other.dtype
3596 
3597         lvalues = self._get_engine_target()
3598         rvalues = other._get_engine_target()
3599 
3600         left_idx, right_idx = _get_join_indexers(
3601             [lvalues], [rvalues], how=how, sort=True
3602         )
3603 
3604         left_idx = ensure_platform_int(left_idx)
3605         right_idx = ensure_platform_int(right_idx)
3606 
3607         join_index = np.asarray(lvalues.take(left_idx))
3608         mask = left_idx == -1
3609         np.putmask(join_index, mask, rvalues.take(right_idx))
3610 
3611         join_index = self._wrap_joined_index(join_index, other)
3612 
3613         if return_indexers:
3614             return join_index, left_idx, right_idx
3615         else:
3616             return join_index
3617 
3618     def _join_level(
3619         self, other, level, how="left", return_indexers=False, keep_order=True
3620     ):
3621         """
3622         The join method *only* affects the level of the resulting
3623         MultiIndex. Otherwise it just exactly aligns the Index data to the
3624         labels of the level in the MultiIndex.
3625 
3626         If ```keep_order == True```, the order of the data indexed by the
3627         MultiIndex will not be changed; otherwise, it will tie out
3628         with `other`.
3629         """
3630         from pandas.core.indexes.multi import MultiIndex
3631 
3632         def _get_leaf_sorter(labels):
3633             """
3634             Returns sorter for the inner most level while preserving the
3635             order of higher levels.
3636             """
3637             if labels[0].size == 0:
3638                 return np.empty(0, dtype="int64")
3639 
3640             if len(labels) == 1:
3641                 lab = ensure_int64(labels[0])
3642                 sorter, _ = libalgos.groupsort_indexer(lab, 1 + lab.max())
3643                 return sorter
3644 
3645             # find indexers of beginning of each set of
3646             # same-key labels w.r.t all but last level
3647             tic = labels[0][:-1] != labels[0][1:]
3648             for lab in labels[1:-1]:
3649                 tic |= lab[:-1] != lab[1:]
3650 
3651             starts = np.hstack(([True], tic, [True])).nonzero()[0]
3652             lab = ensure_int64(labels[-1])
3653             return lib.get_level_sorter(lab, ensure_int64(starts))
3654 
3655         if isinstance(self, MultiIndex) and isinstance(other, MultiIndex):
3656             raise TypeError("Join on level between two MultiIndex objects is ambiguous")
3657 
3658         left, right = self, other
3659 
3660         flip_order = not isinstance(self, MultiIndex)
3661         if flip_order:
3662             left, right = right, left
3663             how = {"right": "left", "left": "right"}.get(how, how)
3664 
3665         level = left._get_level_number(level)
3666         old_level = left.levels[level]
3667 
3668         if not right.is_unique:
3669             raise NotImplementedError(
3670                 "Index._join_level on non-unique index is not implemented"
3671             )
3672 
3673         new_level, left_lev_indexer, right_lev_indexer = old_level.join(
3674             right, how=how, return_indexers=True
3675         )
3676 
3677         if left_lev_indexer is None:
3678             if keep_order or len(left) == 0:
3679                 left_indexer = None
3680                 join_index = left
3681             else:  # sort the leaves
3682                 left_indexer = _get_leaf_sorter(left.codes[: level + 1])
3683                 join_index = left[left_indexer]
3684 
3685         else:
3686             left_lev_indexer = ensure_int64(left_lev_indexer)
3687             rev_indexer = lib.get_reverse_indexer(left_lev_indexer, len(old_level))
3688 
3689             new_lev_codes = algos.take_nd(
3690                 rev_indexer, left.codes[level], allow_fill=False
3691             )
3692 
3693             new_codes = list(left.codes)
3694             new_codes[level] = new_lev_codes
3695 
3696             new_levels = list(left.levels)
3697             new_levels[level] = new_level
3698 
3699             if keep_order:  # just drop missing values. o.w. keep order
3700                 left_indexer = np.arange(len(left), dtype=np.intp)
3701                 mask = new_lev_codes != -1
3702                 if not mask.all():
3703                     new_codes = [lab[mask] for lab in new_codes]
3704                     left_indexer = left_indexer[mask]
3705 
3706             else:  # tie out the order with other
3707                 if level == 0:  # outer most level, take the fast route
3708                     ngroups = 1 + new_lev_codes.max()
3709                     left_indexer, counts = libalgos.groupsort_indexer(
3710                         new_lev_codes, ngroups
3711                     )
3712 
3713                     # missing values are placed first; drop them!
3714                     left_indexer = left_indexer[counts[0] :]
3715                     new_codes = [lab[left_indexer] for lab in new_codes]
3716 
3717                 else:  # sort the leaves
3718                     mask = new_lev_codes != -1
3719                     mask_all = mask.all()
3720                     if not mask_all:
3721                         new_codes = [lab[mask] for lab in new_codes]
3722 
3723                     left_indexer = _get_leaf_sorter(new_codes[: level + 1])
3724                     new_codes = [lab[left_indexer] for lab in new_codes]
3725 
3726                     # left_indexers are w.r.t masked frame.
3727                     # reverse to original frame!
3728                     if not mask_all:
3729                         left_indexer = mask.nonzero()[0][left_indexer]
3730 
3731             join_index = MultiIndex(
3732                 levels=new_levels,
3733                 codes=new_codes,
3734                 names=left.names,
3735                 verify_integrity=False,
3736             )
3737 
3738         if right_lev_indexer is not None:
3739             right_indexer = algos.take_nd(
3740                 right_lev_indexer, join_index.codes[level], allow_fill=False
3741             )
3742         else:
3743             right_indexer = join_index.codes[level]
3744 
3745         if flip_order:
3746             left_indexer, right_indexer = right_indexer, left_indexer
3747 
3748         if return_indexers:
3749             left_indexer = (
3750                 None if left_indexer is None else ensure_platform_int(left_indexer)
3751             )
3752             right_indexer = (
3753                 None if right_indexer is None else ensure_platform_int(right_indexer)
3754             )
3755             return join_index, left_indexer, right_indexer
3756         else:
3757             return join_index
3758 
3759     def _join_monotonic(self, other, how="left", return_indexers=False):
3760         # We only get here with matching dtypes
3761         assert other.dtype == self.dtype
3762 
3763         if self.equals(other):
3764             ret_index = other if how == "right" else self
3765             if return_indexers:
3766                 return ret_index, None, None
3767             else:
3768                 return ret_index
3769 
3770         sv = self._get_engine_target()
3771         ov = other._get_engine_target()
3772 
3773         if self.is_unique and other.is_unique:
3774             # We can perform much better than the general case
3775             if how == "left":
3776                 join_index = self
3777                 lidx = None
3778                 ridx = self._left_indexer_unique(sv, ov)
3779             elif how == "right":
3780                 join_index = other
3781                 lidx = self._left_indexer_unique(ov, sv)
3782                 ridx = None
3783             elif how == "inner":
3784                 join_index, lidx, ridx = self._inner_indexer(sv, ov)
3785                 join_index = self._wrap_joined_index(join_index, other)
3786             elif how == "outer":
3787                 join_index, lidx, ridx = self._outer_indexer(sv, ov)
3788                 join_index = self._wrap_joined_index(join_index, other)
3789         else:
3790             if how == "left":
3791                 join_index, lidx, ridx = self._left_indexer(sv, ov)
3792             elif how == "right":
3793                 join_index, ridx, lidx = self._left_indexer(ov, sv)
3794             elif how == "inner":
3795                 join_index, lidx, ridx = self._inner_indexer(sv, ov)
3796             elif how == "outer":
3797                 join_index, lidx, ridx = self._outer_indexer(sv, ov)
3798             join_index = self._wrap_joined_index(join_index, other)
3799 
3800         if return_indexers:
3801             lidx = None if lidx is None else ensure_platform_int(lidx)
3802             ridx = None if ridx is None else ensure_platform_int(ridx)
3803             return join_index, lidx, ridx
3804         else:
3805             return join_index
3806

3808         name = get_op_result_name(self, other)
3809         return Index(joined, name=name)

3886     def where(self, cond, other=None):
3887         """
3888         Replace values where the condition is False.
3889 
3890         The replacement is taken from other.
3891 
3892         Parameters
3893         ----------
3894         cond : bool array-like with the same length as self
3895             Condition to select the values on.
3896         other : scalar, or array-like, default None
3897             Replacement if the condition is False.
3898 
3899         Returns
3900         -------
3901         pandas.Index
3902             A copy of self with values replaced from other
3903             where the condition is False.
3904 
3905         See Also
3906         --------
3907         Series.where : Same method for Series.
3908         DataFrame.where : Same method for DataFrame.
3909 
3910         Examples
3911         --------
3912         >>> idx = pd.Index(['car', 'bike', 'train', 'tractor'])
3913         >>> idx
3914         Index(['car', 'bike', 'train', 'tractor'], dtype='object')
3915         >>> idx.where(idx.isin(['car', 'train']), 'other')
3916         Index(['car', 'other', 'train', 'other'], dtype='object')
3917         """
3918         if other is None:
3919             other = self._na_value
3920 
3921         dtype = self.dtype
3922         values = self.values
3923 
3924         if is_bool(other) or is_bool_dtype(other):
3925 
3926             # bools force casting
3927             values = values.astype(object)
3928             dtype = None
3929 
3930         values = np.where(cond, values, other)
3931 
3932         if self._is_numeric_dtype and np.any(isna(values)):
3933             # We can't coerce to the numeric dtype of "self" (unless
3934             # it's float) if there are NaN values in our output.
3935             dtype = None
3936 
3937         return Index(values, dtype=dtype, name=self.name)

4012     def __contains__(self, key: Any) -> bool:

4022         -------

4059     def __getitem__(self, key):
4060         """
4061         Override numpy.ndarray's __getitem__ method to work as desired.
4062 
4063         This function adds lists and Series as valid boolean indexers
4064         (ndarrays only supports ndarray with dtype=bool).
4065 
4066         If resulting ndim != 1, plain ndarray is returned instead of
4067         corresponding `Index` subclass.
4068 
4069         """
4070         # There's no custom logic to be implemented in __getslice__, so it's
4071         # not overloaded intentionally.
4072         getitem = self._data.__getitem__
4073         promote = self._shallow_copy
4074 
4075         if is_scalar(key):
4076             key = com.cast_scalar_indexer(key, warn_float=True)
4077             return getitem(key)
4078 
4079         if isinstance(key, slice):
4080             # This case is separated from the conditional above to avoid
4081             # pessimization of basic indexing.
4082             return promote(getitem(key))
4083 
4084         if com.is_bool_indexer(key):
4085             key = np.asarray(key, dtype=bool)
4086 
4087         result = getitem(key)
4088         if not is_scalar(result):
4089             if np.ndim(result) > 1:
4090                 deprecate_ndim_indexing(result)
4091                 return result
4092             return promote(result)
4093         else:
4094             return result
4095 
4096     def _can_hold_identifiers_and_holds_name(self, name) -> bool:
4097         """
4098         Faster check for ``name in self`` when we know `name` is a Python
4099         identifier (e.g. in NDFrame.__getattr__, which hits this to support
4100         . key lookup). For indexes that can't hold identifiers (everything
4101         but object & categorical) we just return False.
4102 
4103         https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/issues/19764
4104         """
4105         if self.is_object() or self.is_categorical():
4106             return name in self
4107         return False

4109     def append(self, other):
4110         """
4111         Append a collection of Index options together.
4112 
4113         Parameters
4114         ----------
4115         other : Index or list/tuple of indices
4116 
4117         Returns
4118         -------
4119         appended : Index
4120         """
4121         to_concat = [self]
4122 
4123         if isinstance(other, (list, tuple)):
4124             to_concat = to_concat + list(other)
4125         else:
4126             to_concat.append(other)
4127 
4128         for obj in to_concat:
4129             if not isinstance(obj, Index):
4130                 raise TypeError("all inputs must be Index")
4131 
4132         names = {obj.name for obj in to_concat}
4133         name = None if len(names) > 1 else self.name
4134 
4135         return self._concat(to_concat, name)

4137     def _concat(self, to_concat, name):
4138         """
4139         Concatenate multiple Index objects.
4140         """
4141         to_concat = [x._values if isinstance(x, Index) else x for x in to_concat]
4142 
4143         result = _concat.concat_compat(to_concat)
4144         return Index(result, name=name)

4146     def putmask(self, mask, value):
4147         """
4148         Return a new Index of the values set with the mask.
4149 
4150         Returns
4151         -------
4152         Index
4153 
4154         See Also
4155         --------
4156         numpy.ndarray.putmask
4157         """
4158         values = self.values.copy()

4160             np.putmask(values, mask, self._convert_for_op(value))
4161             if is_period_dtype(self.dtype):

4172     def equals(self, other: Any) -> bool:
4173         """
4174         Determine if two Index object are equal.
4175 
4176         The things that are being compared are:
4177 
4178         * The elements inside the Index object.
4179         * The order of the elements inside the Index object.
4180 
4181         Parameters
4182         ----------
4183         other : Any
4184             The other object to compare against.
4185 
4186         Returns
4187         -------
4188         bool
4189             True if "other" is an Index and it has the same elements and order
4190             as the calling index; False otherwise.
4191 
4192         Examples
4193         --------
4194         >>> idx1 = pd.Index([1, 2, 3])
4195         >>> idx1
4196         Int64Index([1, 2, 3], dtype='int64')
4197         >>> idx1.equals(pd.Index([1, 2, 3]))
4198         True
4199 
4200         The elements inside are compared
4201 
4202         >>> idx2 = pd.Index(["1", "2", "3"])
4203         >>> idx2
4204         Index(['1', '2', '3'], dtype='object')
4205 
4206         >>> idx1.equals(idx2)
4207         False
4208 
4209         The order is compared
4210 
4211         >>> ascending_idx = pd.Index([1, 2, 3])
4212         >>> ascending_idx
4213         Int64Index([1, 2, 3], dtype='int64')
4214         >>> descending_idx = pd.Index([3, 2, 1])
4215         >>> descending_idx
4216         Int64Index([3, 2, 1], dtype='int64')
4217         >>> ascending_idx.equals(descending_idx)
4218         False
4219 
4220         The dtype is *not* compared
4221 
4222         >>> int64_idx = pd.Int64Index([1, 2, 3])
4223         >>> int64_idx
4224         Int64Index([1, 2, 3], dtype='int64')
4225         >>> uint64_idx = pd.UInt64Index([1, 2, 3])
4226         >>> uint64_idx
4227         UInt64Index([1, 2, 3], dtype='uint64')
4228         >>> int64_idx.equals(uint64_idx)
4229         True
4230         """
4231         if self.is_(other):
4232             return True
4233 
4234         if not isinstance(other, Index):
4235             return False
4236 
4237         if is_object_dtype(self.dtype) and not is_object_dtype(other.dtype):
4238             # if other is not object, use other's logic for coercion
4239             return other.equals(self)
4240 
4241         if isinstance(other, ABCMultiIndex):
4242             # d-level MultiIndex can equal d-tuple Index
4243             return other.equals(self)
4244 
4245         if is_extension_array_dtype(other.dtype):
4246             # All EA-backed Index subclasses override equals
4247             return other.equals(self)
4248 
4249         return array_equivalent(self._values, other._values)
4250 
4251     def identical(self, other) -> bool:
4252         """
4253         Similar to equals, but checks that object attributes and types are also equal.
4254 
4255         Returns
4256         -------
4257         bool
4258             If two Index objects have equal elements and same type True,
4259             otherwise False.
4260         """
4261         return (
4262             self.equals(other)
4263             and all(
4264                 (
4265                     getattr(self, c, None) == getattr(other, c, None)
4266                     for c in self._comparables
4267                 )
4268             )
4269             and type(self) == type(other)
4270         )

4272     def asof(self, label):
4273         """
4274         Return the label from the index, or, if not present, the previous one.
4275 
4276         Assuming that the index is sorted, return the passed index label if it
4277         is in the index, or return the previous index label if the passed one
4278         is not in the index.
4279 
4280         Parameters
4281         ----------
4282         label : object
4283             The label up to which the method returns the latest index label.
4284 
4285         Returns
4286         -------
4287         object
4288             The passed label if it is in the index. The previous label if the
4289             passed label is not in the sorted index or `NaN` if there is no
4290             such label.
4291 
4292         See Also
4293         --------
4294         Series.asof : Return the latest value in a Series up to the
4295             passed index.
4296         merge_asof : Perform an asof merge (similar to left join but it
4297             matches on nearest key rather than equal key).
4298         Index.get_loc : An `asof` is a thin wrapper around `get_loc`
4299             with method='pad'.
4300 
4301         Examples
4302         --------
4303         `Index.asof` returns the latest index label up to the passed label.
4304 
4305         >>> idx = pd.Index(['2013-12-31', '2014-01-02', '2014-01-03'])
4306         >>> idx.asof('2014-01-01')
4307         '2013-12-31'
4308 
4309         If the label is in the index, the method returns the passed label.
4310 
4311         >>> idx.asof('2014-01-02')
4312         '2014-01-02'
4313 
4314         If all of the labels in the index are later than the passed label,
4315         NaN is returned.
4316 
4317         >>> idx.asof('1999-01-02')
4318         nan
4319 
4320         If the index is not sorted, an error is raised.
4321 
4322         >>> idx_not_sorted = pd.Index(['2013-12-31', '2015-01-02',
4323         ...                            '2014-01-03'])
4324         >>> idx_not_sorted.asof('2013-12-31')
4325         Traceback (most recent call last):
4326         ValueError: index must be monotonic increasing or decreasing
4327         """
4328         try:
4329             loc = self.get_loc(label, method="pad")
4330         except KeyError:
4331             return self._na_value
4332         else:
4333             if isinstance(loc, slice):
4334                 loc = loc.indices(len(self))[-1]
4335             return self[loc]
4336 
4337     def asof_locs(self, where, mask):
4338         """
4339         Return the locations (indices) of labels in the index.
4340 
4341         As in the `asof` function, if the label (a particular entry in
4342         `where`) is not in the index, the latest index label up to the
4343         passed label is chosen and its index returned.
4344 
4345         If all of the labels in the index are later than a label in `where`,
4346         -1 is returned.
4347 
4348         `mask` is used to ignore NA values in the index during calculation.
4349 
4350         Parameters
4351         ----------
4352         where : Index
4353             An Index consisting of an array of timestamps.
4354         mask : array-like
4355             Array of booleans denoting where values in the original
4356             data are not NA.
4357 
4358         Returns
4359         -------
4360         numpy.ndarray
4361             An array of locations (indices) of the labels from the Index
4362             which correspond to the return values of the `asof` function
4363             for every element in `where`.
4364         """
4365         locs = self.values[mask].searchsorted(where.values, side="right")
4366         locs = np.where(locs > 0, locs - 1, 0)
4367 
4368         result = np.arange(len(self))[mask].take(locs)
4369 
4370         first = mask.argmax()
4371         result[(locs == 0) & (where.values < self.values[first])] = -1
4372 
4373         return result

4375     def sort_values(
4376         self, return_indexer=False, ascending=True, key: Optional[Callable] = None
4377     ):
4378         """
4379         Return a sorted copy of the index.
4380 
4381         Return a sorted copy of the index, and optionally return the indices
4382         that sorted the index itself.
4383 
4384         Parameters
4385         ----------
4386         return_indexer : bool, default False
4387             Should the indices that would sort the index be returned.
4388         ascending : bool, default True
4389             Should the index values be sorted in an ascending order.
4390         key : callable, optional
4391             If not None, apply the key function to the index values
4392             before sorting. This is similar to the `key` argument in the
4393             builtin :meth:`sorted` function, with the notable difference that
4394             this `key` function should be *vectorized*. It should expect an
4395             ``Index`` and return an ``Index`` of the same shape.
4396 
4397             .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
4398 
4399         Returns
4400         -------
4401         sorted_index : pandas.Index
4402             Sorted copy of the index.
4403         indexer : numpy.ndarray, optional
4404             The indices that the index itself was sorted by.
4405 
4406         See Also
4407         --------
4408         Series.sort_values : Sort values of a Series.
4409         DataFrame.sort_values : Sort values in a DataFrame.
4410 
4411         Examples
4412         --------
4413         >>> idx = pd.Index([10, 100, 1, 1000])
4414         >>> idx
4415         Int64Index([10, 100, 1, 1000], dtype='int64')
4416 
4417         Sort values in ascending order (default behavior).
4418 
4419         >>> idx.sort_values()
4420         Int64Index([1, 10, 100, 1000], dtype='int64')
4421 
4422         Sort values in descending order, and also get the indices `idx` was
4423         sorted by.
4424 
4425         >>> idx.sort_values(ascending=False, return_indexer=True)
4426         (Int64Index([1000, 100, 10, 1], dtype='int64'), array([3, 1, 0, 2]))
4427         """
4428         idx = ensure_key_mapped(self, key)
4429 
4430         _as = idx.argsort()
4431         if not ascending:
4432             _as = _as[::-1]
4433 
4434         sorted_index = self.take(_as)
4435 
4436         if return_indexer:
4437             return sorted_index, _as
4438         else:
4439             return sorted_index

4547     def get_value(self, series: "Series", key):
4548         """
4549         Fast lookup of value from 1-dimensional ndarray.
4550 
4551         Only use this if you know what you're doing.
4552 
4553         Returns
4554         -------
4555         scalar or Series
4556         """
4557         warnings.warn(
4558             "get_value is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. "
4559             "Use Series[key] instead",
4560             FutureWarning,
4561             stacklevel=2,

4563 
4564         self._check_indexing_error(key)
4565 
4566         try:
4567             # GH 20882, 21257
4568             # First try to convert the key to a location
4569             # If that fails, raise a KeyError if an integer

4578                 #  a locational lookup.
4579                 loc = key

4635     _index_shared_docs[

4637     ] = """

4650             positions matches the corresponding target values. Missing values
4651             in the target are marked by -1.

4657     @Appender(_index_shared_docs["get_indexer_non_unique"] % _index_doc_kwargs)
4658     def get_indexer_non_unique(self, target):
4659         target = ensure_index(target)
4660         pself, ptarget = self._maybe_promote(target)
4661         if pself is not self or ptarget is not target:
4662             return pself.get_indexer_non_unique(ptarget)
4663 
4664         if not self._is_comparable_dtype(target.dtype):
4665             no_matches = -1 * np.ones(self.shape, dtype=np.intp)
4666             return no_matches, no_matches
4667 
4668         if is_categorical_dtype(target.dtype):
4669             tgt_values = np.asarray(target)
4670         else:
4671             tgt_values = target._get_engine_target()
4672 
4673         indexer, missing = self._engine.get_indexer_non_unique(tgt_values)
4674         return ensure_platform_int(indexer), missing

4676     def get_indexer_for(self, target, **kwargs):
4677         """
4678         Guaranteed return of an indexer even when non-unique.
4679 
4680         This dispatches to get_indexer or get_indexer_non_unique
4681         as appropriate.
4682 
4683         Returns
4684         -------
4685         numpy.ndarray
4686             List of indices.
4687         """
4688         if self.is_unique:
4689             return self.get_indexer(target, **kwargs)
4690         indexer, _ = self.get_indexer_non_unique(target, **kwargs)
4691         return indexer

4693     def _maybe_promote(self, other: "Index"):
4694         """
4695         When dealing with an object-dtype Index and a non-object Index, see
4696         if we can upcast the object-dtype one to improve performance.
4697         """
4698 
4699         if self.inferred_type == "date" and isinstance(other, ABCDatetimeIndex):
4700             try:
4701                 return type(other)(self), other
4702             except OutOfBoundsDatetime:
4703                 return self, other
4704         elif self.inferred_type == "timedelta" and isinstance(other, ABCTimedeltaIndex):
4705             # TODO: we dont have tests that get here
4706             return type(other)(self), other
4707         elif self.inferred_type == "boolean":
4708             if not is_object_dtype(self.dtype):
4709                 return self.astype("object"), other.astype("object")
4710 
4711         if not is_object_dtype(self.dtype) and is_object_dtype(other.dtype):
4712             # Reverse op so we dont need to re-implement on the subclasses
4713             other, self = other._maybe_promote(self)
4714 
4715         return self, other

4721         return True

4723     def groupby(self, values) -> PrettyDict[Hashable, np.ndarray]:

4749     def map(self, mapper, na_action=None):
4750         """
4751         Map values using input correspondence (a dict, Series, or function).
4752 
4753         Parameters
4754         ----------
4755         mapper : function, dict, or Series
4756             Mapping correspondence.
4757         na_action : {None, 'ignore'}
4758             If 'ignore', propagate NA values, without passing them to the
4759             mapping correspondence.
4760 
4761         Returns
4762         -------
4763         applied : Union[Index, MultiIndex], inferred
4764             The output of the mapping function applied to the index.
4765             If the function returns a tuple with more than one element
4766             a MultiIndex will be returned.
4767         """
4768         from pandas.core.indexes.multi import MultiIndex
4769 
4770         new_values = super()._map_values(mapper, na_action=na_action)
4771 
4772         attributes = self._get_attributes_dict()
4773 
4774         # we can return a MultiIndex
4775         if new_values.size and isinstance(new_values[0], tuple):
4776             if isinstance(self, MultiIndex):
4777                 names = self.names
4778             elif attributes.get("name"):
4779                 names = [attributes.get("name")] * len(new_values[0])
4780             else:
4781                 names = None
4782             return MultiIndex.from_tuples(new_values, names=names)
4783 
4784         attributes["copy"] = False
4785         if not new_values.size:
4786             # empty
4787             attributes["dtype"] = self.dtype
4788 
4789         return Index(new_values, **attributes)

4791     # TODO: De-duplicate with map, xref GH#32349
4792     def _transform_index(self, func, level=None) -> "Index":
4793         """
4794         Apply function to all values found in index.
4795 
4796         This includes transforming multiindex entries separately.
4797         Only apply function to one level of the MultiIndex if level is specified.
4798         """
4799         if isinstance(self, ABCMultiIndex):
4800             if level is not None:
4801                 items = [
4802                     tuple(func(y) if i == level else y for i, y in enumerate(x))
4803                     for x in self
4804                 ]
4805             else:
4806                 items = [tuple(func(y) for y in x) for x in self]
4807             return type(self).from_tuples(items, names=self.names)
4808         else:
4809             items = [func(x) for x in self]
4810             return Index(items, name=self.name, tupleize_cols=False)

4812     def isin(self, values, level=None):
4813         """
4814         Return a boolean array where the index values are in `values`.
4815 
4816         Compute boolean array of whether each index value is found in the
4817         passed set of values. The length of the returned boolean array matches
4818         the length of the index.
4819 
4820         Parameters
4821         ----------
4822         values : set or list-like
4823             Sought values.
4824         level : str or int, optional
4825             Name or position of the index level to use (if the index is a
4826             `MultiIndex`).
4827 
4828         Returns
4829         -------
4830         is_contained : ndarray
4831             NumPy array of boolean values.
4832 
4833         See Also
4834         --------
4835         Series.isin : Same for Series.
4836         DataFrame.isin : Same method for DataFrames.
4837 
4838         Notes
4839         -----
4840         In the case of `MultiIndex` you must either specify `values` as a
4841         list-like object containing tuples that are the same length as the
4842         number of levels, or specify `level`. Otherwise it will raise a
4843         ``ValueError``.
4844 
4845         If `level` is specified:
4846 
4847         - if it is the name of one *and only one* index level, use that level;
4848         - otherwise it should be a number indicating level position.
4849 
4850         Examples
4851         --------
4852         >>> idx = pd.Index([1,2,3])
4853         >>> idx
4854         Int64Index([1, 2, 3], dtype='int64')
4855 
4856         Check whether each index value in a list of values.
4857 
4858         >>> idx.isin([1, 4])
4859         array([ True, False, False])
4860 
4861         >>> midx = pd.MultiIndex.from_arrays([[1,2,3],
4862         ...                                  ['red', 'blue', 'green']],
4863         ...                                  names=('number', 'color'))
4864         >>> midx
4865         MultiIndex([(1,   'red'),
4866                     (2,  'blue'),
4867                     (3, 'green')],
4868                    names=['number', 'color'])
4869 
4870         Check whether the strings in the 'color' level of the MultiIndex
4871         are in a list of colors.
4872 
4873         >>> midx.isin(['red', 'orange', 'yellow'], level='color')
4874         array([ True, False, False])
4875 
4876         To check across the levels of a MultiIndex, pass a list of tuples:
4877 
4878         >>> midx.isin([(1, 'red'), (3, 'red')])
4879         array([ True, False, False])
4880 
4881         For a DatetimeIndex, string values in `values` are converted to
4882         Timestamps.
4883 
4884         >>> dates = ['2000-03-11', '2000-03-12', '2000-03-13']
4885         >>> dti = pd.to_datetime(dates)
4886         >>> dti
4887         DatetimeIndex(['2000-03-11', '2000-03-12', '2000-03-13'],
4888         dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq=None)
4889 
4890         >>> dti.isin(['2000-03-11'])
4891         array([ True, False, False])
4892         """
4893         if level is not None:
4894             self._validate_index_level(level)
4895         return algos.isin(self, values)

4902     def slice_indexer(self, start=None, end=None, step=None, kind=None):
4903         """
4904         Compute the slice indexer for input labels and step.
4905 
4906         Index needs to be ordered and unique.
4907 
4908         Parameters
4909         ----------
4910         start : label, default None
4911             If None, defaults to the beginning.
4912         end : label, default None
4913             If None, defaults to the end.
4914         step : int, default None
4915         kind : str, default None
4916 
4917         Returns
4918         -------
4919         indexer : slice
4920 
4921         Raises
4922         ------
4923         KeyError : If key does not exist, or key is not unique and index is
4924             not ordered.
4925 
4926         Notes
4927         -----
4928         This function assumes that the data is sorted, so use at your own peril
4929 
4930         Examples
4931         --------
4932         This is a method on all index types. For example you can do:
4933 
4934         >>> idx = pd.Index(list('abcd'))
4935         >>> idx.slice_indexer(start='b', end='c')
4936         slice(1, 3, None)
4937 
4938         >>> idx = pd.MultiIndex.from_arrays([list('abcd'), list('efgh')])
4939         >>> idx.slice_indexer(start='b', end=('c', 'g'))
4940         slice(1, 3, None)
4941         """
4942         start_slice, end_slice = self.slice_locs(start, end, step=step, kind=kind)
4943 
4944         # return a slice
4945         if not is_scalar(start_slice):
4946             raise AssertionError("Start slice bound is non-scalar")
4947         if not is_scalar(end_slice):
4948             raise AssertionError("End slice bound is non-scalar")
4949 
4950         return slice(start_slice, end_slice, step)

4975     def _maybe_cast_slice_bound(self, label, side: str_t, kind):
4976         """
4977         This function should be overloaded in subclasses that allow non-trivial
4978         casting on label-slice bounds, e.g. datetime-like indices allowing
4979         strings containing formatted datetimes.
4980 
4981         Parameters
4982         ----------
4983         label : object
4984         side : {'left', 'right'}
4985         kind : {'loc', 'getitem'} or None
4986 
4987         Returns
4988         -------
4989         label : object
4990 
4991         Notes
4992         -----
4993         Value of `side` parameter should be validated in caller.
4994         """
4995         assert kind in ["loc", "getitem", None]
4996 
4997         # We are a plain index here (sub-class override this method if they
4998         # wish to have special treatment for floats/ints, e.g. Float64Index and
4999         # datetimelike Indexes
5000         # reject them
5001         if is_float(label):
5002             self._invalid_indexer("slice", label)
5003 
5004         # we are trying to find integer bounds on a non-integer based index
5005         # this is rejected (generally .loc gets you here)
5006         elif is_integer(label):
5007             self._invalid_indexer("slice", label)
5008 
5009         return label

5011     def _searchsorted_monotonic(self, label, side="left"):
5012         if self.is_monotonic_increasing:
5013             return self.searchsorted(label, side=side)
5014         elif self.is_monotonic_decreasing:
5015             # np.searchsorted expects ascending sort order, have to reverse
5016             # everything for it to work (element ordering, search side and
5017             # resulting value).
5018             pos = self[::-1].searchsorted(
5019                 label, side="right" if side == "left" else "left"
5020             )
5021             return len(self) - pos
5022 
5023         raise ValueError("index must be monotonic increasing or decreasing")
5024 
5025     def get_slice_bound(self, label, side: str_t, kind) -> int:
5026         """
5027         Calculate slice bound that corresponds to given label.
5028 
5029         Returns leftmost (one-past-the-rightmost if ``side=='right'``) position
5030         of given label.
5031 
5032         Parameters
5033         ----------
5034         label : object
5035         side : {'left', 'right'}
5036         kind : {'loc', 'getitem'} or None
5037 
5038         Returns
5039         -------
5040         int
5041             Index of label.
5042         """
5043         assert kind in ["loc", "getitem", None]
5044 
5045         if side not in ("left", "right"):
5046             raise ValueError(
5047                 "Invalid value for side kwarg, must be either "
5048                 f"'left' or 'right': {side}"
5049             )
5050 
5051         original_label = label
5052 
5053         # For datetime indices label may be a string that has to be converted
5054         # to datetime boundary according to its resolution.
5055         label = self._maybe_cast_slice_bound(label, side, kind)
5056 
5057         # we need to look up the label
5058         try:
5059             slc = self.get_loc(label)
5060         except KeyError as err:
5061             try:
5062                 return self._searchsorted_monotonic(label, side)
5063             except ValueError:
5064                 # raise the original KeyError
5065                 raise err
5066 
5067         if isinstance(slc, np.ndarray):
5068             # get_loc may return a boolean array or an array of indices, which
5069             # is OK as long as they are representable by a slice.
5070             if is_bool_dtype(slc):
5071                 slc = lib.maybe_booleans_to_slice(slc.view("u1"))
5072             else:
5073                 slc = lib.maybe_indices_to_slice(slc.astype("i8"), len(self))
5074             if isinstance(slc, np.ndarray):
5075                 raise KeyError(
5076                     f"Cannot get {side} slice bound for non-unique "
5077                     f"label: {repr(original_label)}"
5078                 )
5079 
5080         if isinstance(slc, slice):
5081             if side == "left":
5082                 return slc.start
5083             else:
5084                 return slc.stop
5085         else:
5086             if side == "right":
5087                 return slc + 1
5088             else:
5089                 return slc

5091     def slice_locs(self, start=None, end=None, step=None, kind=None):
5092         """
5093         Compute slice locations for input labels.
5094 
5095         Parameters
5096         ----------
5097         start : label, default None
5098             If None, defaults to the beginning.
5099         end : label, default None
5100             If None, defaults to the end.
5101         step : int, defaults None
5102             If None, defaults to 1.
5103         kind : {'loc', 'getitem'} or None
5104 
5105         Returns
5106         -------
5107         start, end : int
5108 
5109         See Also
5110         --------
5111         Index.get_loc : Get location for a single label.
5112 
5113         Notes
5114         -----
5115         This method only works if the index is monotonic or unique.
5116 
5117         Examples
5118         --------
5119         >>> idx = pd.Index(list('abcd'))
5120         >>> idx.slice_locs(start='b', end='c')
5121         (1, 3)
5122         """
5123         inc = step is None or step >= 0
5124 
5125         if not inc:
5126             # If it's a reverse slice, temporarily swap bounds.
5127             start, end = end, start
5128 
5129         # GH 16785: If start and end happen to be date strings with UTC offsets
5130         # attempt to parse and check that the offsets are the same
5131         if isinstance(start, (str, datetime)) and isinstance(end, (str, datetime)):
5132             try:
5133                 ts_start = Timestamp(start)
5134                 ts_end = Timestamp(end)
5135             except (ValueError, TypeError):
5136                 pass
5137             else:
5138                 if not tz_compare(ts_start.tzinfo, ts_end.tzinfo):
5139                     raise ValueError("Both dates must have the same UTC offset")
5140 
5141         start_slice = None
5142         if start is not None:
5143             start_slice = self.get_slice_bound(start, "left", kind)
5144         if start_slice is None:
5145             start_slice = 0
5146 
5147         end_slice = None
5148         if end is not None:
5149             end_slice = self.get_slice_bound(end, "right", kind)
5150         if end_slice is None:
5151             end_slice = len(self)
5152 
5153         if not inc:
5154             # Bounds at this moment are swapped, swap them back and shift by 1.
5155             #
5156             # slice_locs('B', 'A', step=-1): s='B', e='A'
5157             #
5158             #              s='A'                 e='B'
5159             # AFTER SWAP:    |                     |
5160             #                v ------------------> V
5161             #           -----------------------------------
5162             #           | | |A|A|A|A| | | | | |B|B| | | | |
5163             #           -----------------------------------
5164             #              ^ <------------------ ^
5165             # SHOULD BE:   |                     |
5166             #           end=s-1              start=e-1
5167             #
5168             end_slice, start_slice = start_slice - 1, end_slice - 1
5169 
5170             # i == -1 triggers ``len(self) + i`` selection that points to the
5171             # last element, not before-the-first one, subtracting len(self)
5172             # compensates that.
5173             if end_slice == -1:
5174                 end_slice -= len(self)
5175             if start_slice == -1:
5176                 start_slice -= len(self)
5177 
5178         return start_slice, end_slice

5211     def insert(self, loc: int, item):

5233     def drop(self, labels, errors: str_t = "raise"):
5234         """
5235         Make new Index with passed list of labels deleted.
5236 
5237         Parameters
5238         ----------
5239         labels : array-like
5240         errors : {'ignore', 'raise'}, default 'raise'
5241             If 'ignore', suppress error and existing labels are dropped.
5242 
5243         Returns
5244         -------
5245         dropped : Index
5246 
5247         Raises
5248         ------
5249         KeyError
5250             If not all of the labels are found in the selected axis
5251         """
5252         arr_dtype = "object" if self.dtype == "object" else None
5253         labels = com.index_labels_to_array(labels, dtype=arr_dtype)
5254         indexer = self.get_indexer(labels)
5255         mask = indexer == -1
5256         if mask.any():
5257             if errors != "ignore":
5258                 raise KeyError(f"{labels[mask]} not found in axis")
5259             indexer = indexer[~mask]
5260         return self.delete(indexer)

5396 
5397         >>> pd.Index([1, 2, 3]).all()
5398         True
5399 
5400         False, because ``0`` is considered False.
5401 
5402         >>> pd.Index([0, 1, 2]).all()
5403         False
5404 
5405         **any**
5406 
5407         True, because ``1`` is considered True.
5408 
5409         >>> pd.Index([0, 0, 1]).any()
5410         True
5411 
5412         False, because ``0`` is considered False.
5413 
5414         >>> pd.Index([0, 0, 0]).any()
5415         False
5416         """
5417         )
5418 
5419         _index_shared_docs["index_any"] = dedent(
5420             """
5421 
5422         See Also
5423         --------
5424         Index.all : Return whether all elements are True.
5425         Series.all : Return whether all elements are True.
5426 
5427         Notes
5428         -----
5429         Not a Number (NaN), positive infinity and negative infinity
5430         evaluate to True because these are not equal to zero.
5431 
5432         Examples
5433         --------
5434         >>> index = pd.Index([0, 1, 2])
5435         >>> index.any()
5436         True
5437 
5438         >>> index = pd.Index([0, 0, 0])
5439         >>> index.any()
5440         False
5441         """
5442         )
5443 
5444         def _make_logical_function(name: str_t, desc: str_t, f):
5445             @Substitution(outname=name, desc=desc)
5446             @Appender(_index_shared_docs["index_" + name])
5447             @Appender(_doc)
5448             def logical_func(self, *args, **kwargs):
5449                 result = f(self.values)
5450                 if (
5451                     isinstance(result, (np.ndarray, ABCSeries, Index))
5452                     and result.ndim == 0
5453                 ):
5454                     # return NumPy type
5455                     return result.dtype.type(result.item())
5456                 else:  # pragma: no cover
5457                     return result
5458 
5459             logical_func.__name__ = name
5460             return logical_func
5461 
5462         cls.all = _make_logical_function(
5463             "all", "Return whether all elements are True.", np.all
5464         )
5465         cls.any = _make_logical_function(
5466             "any", "Return whether any element is True.", np.any
5467         )
5468 
5469     @classmethod
5470     def _add_logical_methods_disabled(cls):
5471         """
5472         Add in logical methods to disable.
5473         """
5474         cls.all = make_invalid_op("all")
5475         cls.any = make_invalid_op("any")
5476 
5477     @property
5478     def shape(self):
5479         """
5480         Return a tuple of the shape of the underlying data.
5481         """
5482         # not using "(len(self), )" to return "correct" shape if the values
5483         # consists of a >1 D array (see GH-27775)
5484         # overridden in MultiIndex.shape to avoid materializing the values
5485         return self._values.shape

5490 Index._add_comparison_methods()

5493 def ensure_index_from_sequences(sequences, names=None):
5494     """
5495     Construct an index from sequences of data.
5496 
5497     A single sequence returns an Index. Many sequences returns a
5498     MultiIndex.
5499 
5500     Parameters
5501     ----------
5502     sequences : sequence of sequences
5503     names : sequence of str
5504 
5505     Returns
5506     -------
5507     index : Index or MultiIndex
5508 
5509     Examples
5510     --------
5511     >>> ensure_index_from_sequences([[1, 2, 3]], names=["name"])
5512     Int64Index([1, 2, 3], dtype='int64', name='name')
5513 
5514     >>> ensure_index_from_sequences([["a", "a"], ["a", "b"]], names=["L1", "L2"])
5515     MultiIndex([('a', 'a'),
5516                 ('a', 'b')],
5517                names=['L1', 'L2'])
5518 
5519     See Also
5520     --------
5521     ensure_index
5522     """
5523     from pandas.core.indexes.multi import MultiIndex
5524 
5525     if len(sequences) == 1:
5526         if names is not None:
5527             names = names[0]
5528         return Index(sequences[0], name=names)
5529     else:
5530         return MultiIndex.from_arrays(sequences, names=names)

5533 def ensure_index(index_like, copy: bool = False):
5534     """
5535     Ensure that we have an index from some index-like object.
5536 
5537     Parameters
5538     ----------
5539     index_like : sequence
5540         An Index or other sequence
5541     copy : bool, default False
5542 
5543     Returns
5544     -------
5545     index : Index or MultiIndex
5546 
5547     See Also
5548     --------
5549     ensure_index_from_sequences
5550 
5551     Examples
5552     --------
5553     >>> ensure_index(['a', 'b'])
5554     Index(['a', 'b'], dtype='object')
5555 
5556     >>> ensure_index([('a', 'a'),  ('b', 'c')])
5557     Index([('a', 'a'), ('b', 'c')], dtype='object')
5558 
5559     >>> ensure_index([['a', 'a'], ['b', 'c']])
5560     MultiIndex([('a', 'b'),
5561             ('a', 'c')],
5562            )
5563     """
5564     if isinstance(index_like, Index):
5565         if copy:
5566             index_like = index_like.copy()
5567         return index_like
5568     if hasattr(index_like, "name"):
5569         return Index(index_like, name=index_like.name, copy=copy)
5570 
5571     if is_iterator(index_like):
5572         index_like = list(index_like)
5573 
5574     # must check for exactly list here because of strict type
5575     # check in clean_index_list
5576     if isinstance(index_like, list):
5577         if type(index_like) != list:
5578             index_like = list(index_like)
5579 
5580         converted, all_arrays = lib.clean_index_list(index_like)
5581 
5582         if len(converted) > 0 and all_arrays:
5583             from pandas.core.indexes.multi import MultiIndex
5584 
5585             return MultiIndex.from_arrays(converted)
5586         else:
5587             index_like = converted
5588     else:
5589         # clean_index_list does the equivalent of copying
5590         # so only need to do this if not list instance
5591         if copy:
5592             index_like = copy_func(index_like)
5593 
5594     return Index(index_like)

5600     """

5603     except TypeError:

5609 def _trim_front(strings):
5610     """
5611     Trims zeros and decimal points.
5612     """
5613     trimmed = strings
5614     while len(strings) > 0 and all(x[0] == " " for x in trimmed):
5615         trimmed = [x[1:] for x in trimmed]
5616     return trimmed

5630 def maybe_extract_name(name, obj, cls) -> Label:
5631     """
5632     If no name is passed, then extract it from data, validating hashability.
5633     """
5634     if name is None and isinstance(obj, (Index, ABCSeries)):
5635         # Note we don't just check for "name" attribute since that would
5636         #  pick up e.g. dtype.name
5637         name = obj.name
5638 
5639     # GH#29069
5640     if not is_hashable(name):
5641         raise TypeError(f"{cls.__name__}.name must be a hashable type")
5642 
5643     return name

5646 def _maybe_cast_with_dtype(data: np.ndarray, dtype: np.dtype, copy: bool) -> np.ndarray:
5647     """
5648     If a dtype is passed, cast to the closest matching dtype that is supported
5649     by Index.
5650 
5651     Parameters
5652     ----------
5653     data : np.ndarray
5654     dtype : np.dtype
5655     copy : bool
5656 
5657     Returns
5658     -------
5659     np.ndarray
5660     """
5661     # we need to avoid having numpy coerce
5662     # things that look like ints/floats to ints unless
5663     # they are actually ints, e.g. '0' and 0.0
5664     # should not be coerced
5665     # GH 11836
5666     if is_integer_dtype(dtype):
5667         inferred = lib.infer_dtype(data, skipna=False)
5668         if inferred == "integer":
5669             data = maybe_cast_to_integer_array(data, dtype, copy=copy)
5670         elif inferred in ["floating", "mixed-integer-float"]:
5671             if isna(data).any():
5672                 raise ValueError("cannot convert float NaN to integer")
5673 
5674             if inferred == "mixed-integer-float":
5675                 data = maybe_cast_to_integer_array(data, dtype)
5676 
5677             # If we are actually all equal to integers,
5678             # then coerce to integer.
5679             try:
5680                 data = _try_convert_to_int_array(data, copy, dtype)
5681             except ValueError:
5682                 data = np.array(data, dtype=np.float64, copy=copy)
5683 
5684         elif inferred == "string":
5685             pass
5686         else:
5687             data = data.astype(dtype)
5688     elif is_float_dtype(dtype):
5689         inferred = lib.infer_dtype(data, skipna=False)
5690         if inferred == "string":
5691             pass
5692         else:
5693             data = data.astype(dtype)
5694     else:
5695         data = np.array(data, dtype=dtype, copy=copy)
5696 
5697     return data

5699 
5700 def _maybe_cast_data_without_dtype(subarr):
5701     """
5702     If we have an arraylike input but no passed dtype, try to infer
5703     a supported dtype.
5704 
5705     Parameters
5706     ----------
5707     subarr : np.ndarray, Index, or Series
5708 
5709     Returns
5710     -------
5711     converted : np.ndarray or ExtensionArray
5712     dtype : np.dtype or ExtensionDtype
5713     """
5714     # Runtime import needed bc IntervalArray imports Index
5715     from pandas.core.arrays import (
5716         IntervalArray,
5717         PeriodArray,
5718         DatetimeArray,
5719         TimedeltaArray,
5720     )
5721 
5722     inferred = lib.infer_dtype(subarr, skipna=False)
5723 
5724     if inferred == "integer":
5725         try:
5726             data = _try_convert_to_int_array(subarr, False, None)
5727             return data, data.dtype
5728         except ValueError:
5729             pass
5730 
5731         return subarr, object
5732 
5733     elif inferred in ["floating", "mixed-integer-float", "integer-na"]:
5734         # TODO: Returns IntegerArray for integer-na case in the future
5735         return subarr, np.float64
5736 
5737     elif inferred == "interval":
5738         try:
5739             data = IntervalArray._from_sequence(subarr, copy=False)
5740             return data, data.dtype
5741         except ValueError:
5742             # GH27172: mixed closed Intervals --> object dtype
5743             pass
5744     elif inferred == "boolean":
5745         # don't support boolean explicitly ATM
5746         pass
5747     elif inferred != "string":
5748         if inferred.startswith("datetime"):
5749             try:
5750                 data = DatetimeArray._from_sequence(subarr, copy=False)
5751                 return data, data.dtype
5752             except (ValueError, OutOfBoundsDatetime):
5753                 # GH 27011
5754                 # If we have mixed timezones, just send it
5755                 # down the base constructor
5756                 pass
5757 
5758         elif inferred.startswith("timedelta"):
5759             data = TimedeltaArray._from_sequence(subarr, copy=False)
5760             return data, data.dtype
5761         elif inferred == "period":
5762             try:
5763                 data = PeriodArray._from_sequence(subarr)
5764                 return data, data.dtype
5765             except IncompatibleFrequency:
5766                 pass
5767 
5768     return subarr, subarr.dtype

5771 def _try_convert_to_int_array(
5772     data: np.ndarray, copy: bool, dtype: np.dtype
5773 ) -> np.ndarray:
5774     """
5775     Attempt to convert an array of data into an integer array.
5776 
5777     Parameters
5778     ----------
5779     data : The data to convert.
5780     copy : bool
5781         Whether to copy the data or not.
5782     dtype : np.dtype
5783 
5784     Returns
5785     -------
5786     int_array : data converted to either an ndarray[int64] or ndarray[uint64]
5787 
5788     Raises
5789     ------
5790     ValueError if the conversion was not successful.
5791     """
5792     if not is_unsigned_integer_dtype(dtype):
5793         # skip int64 conversion attempt if uint-like dtype is passed, as
5794         # this could return Int64Index when UInt64Index is what's desired
5795         try:
5796             res = data.astype("i8", copy=False)
5797             if (res == data).all():
5798                 return res  # TODO: might still need to copy
5799         except (OverflowError, TypeError, ValueError):
5800             pass
5801 
5802     # Conversion to int64 failed (possibly due to overflow) or was skipped,
5803     # so let's try now with uint64.
5804     try:
5805         res = data.astype("u8", copy=False)
5806         if (res == data).all():
5807             return res  # TODO: might still need to copy
5808     except (OverflowError, TypeError, ValueError):
5809         pass
5810 
5811     raise ValueError

5814 def _maybe_asobject(dtype, klass, data, copy: bool, name: Label, **kwargs):
5815     """
5816     If an object dtype was specified, create the non-object Index
5817     and then convert it to object.
5818 
5819     Parameters
5820     ----------
5821     dtype : np.dtype, ExtensionDtype, str
5822     klass : Index subclass
5823     data : list-like
5824     copy : bool
5825     name : hashable
5826     **kwargs
5827 
5828     Returns
5829     -------
5830     Index
5831 
5832     Notes
5833     -----
5834     We assume that calling .astype(object) on this klass will make a copy.
5835     """
5836 
5837     # GH#23524 passing `dtype=object` to DatetimeIndex is invalid,
5838     #  will raise in the where `data` is already tz-aware.  So
5839     #  we leave it out of this step and cast to object-dtype after
5840     #  the DatetimeIndex construction.
5841 
5842     if is_dtype_equal(_o_dtype, dtype):
5843         # Note we can pass copy=False because the .astype below
5844         #  will always make a copy
5845         index = klass(data, copy=False, name=name, **kwargs)
5846         return index.astype(object)
5847 
5848     return klass(data, dtype=dtype, copy=copy, name=name, **kwargs)
